1
00:00:14,014 --> 00:00:16,383
We're here with the two lovely villains,

2
00:00:16,449 --> 00:00:19,185
actors Rhee Min-jung and Yoo Ji-tae.

3
00:00:19,252 --> 00:00:22,956
Not only is Ji-tae active as an actor,

4
00:00:23,023 --> 00:00:25,358
<i>-but he's also a film director…</i>
<i>-That's right.</i>

5
00:00:25,425 --> 00:00:28,862
<i>-…and a professor at a university.</i>
-He's a professor?

6
00:00:28,928 --> 00:00:30,163
<i>How impressive.</i>

7
00:00:30,230 --> 00:00:31,998
I've been keeping busy.

8
00:00:32,065 --> 00:00:33,666
-Are you a full-time professor?
-I am.

9
00:00:33,733 --> 00:00:34,567
Full-time?

10
00:00:34,634 --> 00:00:36,236
I've been teaching acting

11
00:00:36,302 --> 00:00:38,004
as well as filmmaking.

12
00:00:38,571 --> 00:00:40,607
Even theater production.

13
00:00:40,673 --> 00:00:42,075
Those sound like courses

14
00:00:42,142 --> 00:00:45,045
they must pass to earn credit
toward their graduation.

15
00:00:45,111 --> 00:00:46,980
I guess that's true.

16
00:00:47,047 --> 00:00:49,249
He might grade the chefs today.

17
00:00:49,315 --> 00:00:51,017
-He's about to.
-You're right!

18
00:00:51,084 --> 00:00:53,453
-He'll be coldhearted.
-Grade him as A, B, or C?

19
00:00:53,520 --> 00:00:54,654
-You're right.
-"You get an F."

20
00:00:54,721 --> 00:00:56,456
I'll just go for a B plus.

21
00:00:56,523 --> 00:00:58,591
It's difficult
to evaluate the artistic aspects,

22
00:00:58,658 --> 00:01:00,293
just as it is difficult to judge a dish.

23
00:01:00,360 --> 00:01:01,761
So it's mostly attendance

24
00:01:01,828 --> 00:01:03,563
-and participation.
-Participation.

25
00:01:03,630 --> 00:01:05,865
I give out quite a lot of assignments.

26
00:01:05,932 --> 00:01:08,334
Professors who give out
a lot of assignments are the worst.

27
00:01:08,401 --> 00:01:09,369
It's tough for the students.

28
00:01:09,769 --> 00:01:11,471
WHAT KIND OF ASSIGNMENTS
WILL HE GIVE OUT TODAY?

29
00:01:11,538 --> 00:01:13,073
Are we doing a group project today?

30
00:01:13,139 --> 00:01:14,474
-I'm scared.
-Many of our chefs

31
00:01:14,541 --> 00:01:16,876
are huge fans of Ji-tae.

32
00:01:17,610 --> 00:01:18,978
Wait a minute.

33
00:01:19,045 --> 00:01:22,248
Sung-jun, once again,
it says you consider Ji-tae…

34
00:01:22,315 --> 00:01:24,284
-Again?
-…a role model.

35
00:01:24,350 --> 00:01:26,352
-Why do you have so many of them?
-How many have you got?

36
00:01:26,419 --> 00:01:27,821
-You must get confused.
-This early in the year?

37
00:01:27,887 --> 00:01:28,888
Why are there so many?

38
00:01:28,955 --> 00:01:31,124
I really love him as an actor,

39
00:01:31,191 --> 00:01:32,759
and I especially loved his performance

40
00:01:32,826 --> 00:01:34,461
in <i>ATGS</i>.

41
00:01:34,527 --> 00:01:36,629
<i>-Attack the Gas Station.</i>
<i>-Attack the Gas Station.</i>

42
00:01:36,696 --> 00:01:38,565
-You were too young.
-How old were you?

43
00:01:38,631 --> 00:01:40,233
-He memorized that.
-Three or four years old?

44
00:01:40,300 --> 00:01:42,001
-Or before he was born?
-Three or four?

45
00:01:42,068 --> 00:01:43,670
You weren't old enough for it.

46
00:01:43,736 --> 00:01:46,106
-I watched it at a video rental room.
-A video rental place?

47
00:01:46,172 --> 00:01:48,575
-A video rental room?
-A video rental room?

48
00:01:48,641 --> 00:01:51,077
I rented it out.
I was too young when it came out.

49
00:01:51,144 --> 00:01:53,113
The aesthetic I strive to achieve

50
00:01:53,179 --> 00:01:55,748
tends to be the rough and tough
testosterone-heavy men,

51
00:01:55,815 --> 00:01:57,417
so you're an inspiration.

52
00:01:57,484 --> 00:01:58,718
But as for me,

53
00:01:58,785 --> 00:02:00,386
I loved him in <i>One Fine Spring Day.</i>

54
00:02:00,453 --> 00:02:02,155
<i>-OFSD.</i>
-I watch it at least four times a year,

55
00:02:02,222 --> 00:02:04,190
at least once a quarter.

56
00:02:04,257 --> 00:02:06,059
-"How can love change?"
-You know what?

57
00:02:06,126 --> 00:02:09,829
Hyun-suk also wrote down Ji-tae
as someone he aspires to be.

58
00:02:09,896 --> 00:02:10,730
I did.

59
00:02:10,797 --> 00:02:13,133
He once visited my restaurant

60
00:02:13,199 --> 00:02:14,267
near Konkuk University.

61
00:02:14,334 --> 00:02:15,168
ME?

62
00:02:15,235 --> 00:02:16,402
I gave him something on the house,

63
00:02:16,469 --> 00:02:18,738
-and although we had lots of guests…
-Something on the house?

64
00:02:18,805 --> 00:02:21,141
Who's going to remember
that you gave them some free food?

65
00:02:21,207 --> 00:02:22,275
-Wait.
-It's just some food.

66
00:02:22,342 --> 00:02:23,676
I came by to say hello myself.

67
00:02:23,743 --> 00:02:25,778
-You did?
-I was a huge fan.

68
00:02:25,845 --> 00:02:26,779
-Oh, my.
-He can't recall.

69
00:02:26,846 --> 00:02:28,214
OH, MY, WHAT DO I DO NOW?

70
00:02:28,281 --> 00:02:30,950
-But…
-He should've done the salt performance.

71
00:02:31,017 --> 00:02:33,853
Anyway, he seemed poised
as he walked out slowly,

72
00:02:33,920 --> 00:02:35,288
yet he had this presence,

73
00:02:35,355 --> 00:02:38,158
so I wanted to be like him.

74
00:02:38,224 --> 00:02:39,058
In 2026?

75
00:02:39,125 --> 00:02:42,428
This year, I'll cook as Choi Ji-tae.

76
00:02:42,495 --> 00:02:43,730
PFFT-HAHAHA

77
00:02:43,796 --> 00:02:45,665
Let's move on to the next question.

78
00:02:45,732 --> 00:02:49,102
The chef who was the most excited
to hear about Ji-tae's visit

79
00:02:49,169 --> 00:02:51,604
-was Eun-yeong.
-Yes, it's me.

80
00:02:51,671 --> 00:02:53,573
-I had to point it out.
-She won't stop smiling.

81
00:02:53,640 --> 00:02:55,108
I always thought of him

82
00:02:55,175 --> 00:02:57,277
as the definition of a mature man.

83
00:02:57,343 --> 00:02:59,479
-A mature man.
-The definition of a mature man.

84
00:02:59,546 --> 00:03:01,948
My favorite work of his

85
00:03:02,015 --> 00:03:03,016
is <i>Midnight FM.</i>

86
00:03:03,082 --> 00:03:04,384
-<i>Midnight FM?</i>
-Yes.

87
00:03:04,450 --> 00:03:06,986
It hit me very deeply.

88
00:03:07,053 --> 00:03:09,722
-I was a villain in that film.
-Yes.

89
00:03:09,789 --> 00:03:11,758
-That's why she's a maniac.
-That defined men for her?

90
00:03:11,824 --> 00:03:15,061
-That's why she's a successful maniac.
-That was the definition of mature men?

91
00:03:15,128 --> 00:03:16,729
So that's what you're into.

92
00:03:16,796 --> 00:03:18,064
THE TASTE OF A MANIAC…

93
00:03:18,131 --> 00:03:21,134
It's because I've been spending some time
with the men here.

94
00:03:21,201 --> 00:03:24,170
-They're all so talkative.
-They're immature.

95
00:03:24,737 --> 00:03:25,638
THE RESERVED MATURE MAN

96
00:03:25,705 --> 00:03:28,841
That's the side
Chef Hyun-suk aspires to have.

97
00:03:28,908 --> 00:03:29,809
-No way.
-Impossible.

98
00:03:29,876 --> 00:03:31,344
Is that why you've been

99
00:03:31,844 --> 00:03:33,313
in this pose?

100
00:03:33,580 --> 00:03:36,382
YOU ARE RIGHT

101
00:03:36,950 --> 00:03:40,320
I have great news from Chef Hyun-suk.

102
00:03:40,386 --> 00:03:42,488
Within 2026, he's expected to become

103
00:03:42,555 --> 00:03:43,957
a grandfather.

104
00:03:44,023 --> 00:03:46,793
CHOI HYUN-SUK WILL BE A GRANDFATHER…
HIS DAUGHTER, CHOI YEON-SOO, IS PREGNANT

105
00:03:46,859 --> 00:03:47,694
A grandpa.

106
00:03:48,795 --> 00:03:51,397
-This is great news.
-My gosh. Yes, it is!

107
00:03:52,165 --> 00:03:53,166
Yes.

108
00:03:55,335 --> 00:03:56,836
Do you know the gender yet?

109
00:03:56,903 --> 00:03:57,737
Yes.

110
00:03:57,804 --> 00:03:59,872
-We do know the gender.
-Already?

111
00:03:59,939 --> 00:04:01,708
I only had two daughters, so…

112
00:04:01,774 --> 00:04:03,076
-Is she having a son?
-Yes, it's a son.

113
00:04:03,142 --> 00:04:06,246
-You'll have a grandson. Goodness.
-I see.

114
00:04:06,312 --> 00:04:07,914
So I hope to bring him up

115
00:04:07,981 --> 00:04:10,083
-as a baseball player.
-A baseball player.

116
00:04:10,149 --> 00:04:11,484
-So…
-Not as a chef?

117
00:04:11,551 --> 00:04:12,552
He has a baby bump nickname,

118
00:04:12,619 --> 00:04:14,587
-What is it?
-but I changed it.

119
00:04:14,654 --> 00:04:15,655
I don't remember theirs.

120
00:04:15,722 --> 00:04:17,523
THE GRANDPA CHANGED HIS NICKNAME

121
00:04:17,590 --> 00:04:19,559
When you're the grandpa?

122
00:04:19,626 --> 00:04:21,628
-And?
-He's nicknamed Choitani now.

123
00:04:21,694 --> 00:04:22,829
-I was going to say.
-Choitani?

124
00:04:22,895 --> 00:04:24,597
-He can both pitch and hit.
-Choitani?

125
00:04:24,664 --> 00:04:26,199
As in Shohei Ohtani?

126
00:04:26,266 --> 00:04:28,101
-Oh, Choitani.
-I told them

127
00:04:28,167 --> 00:04:30,536
that I'd bring the boy up
as a baseball player.

128
00:04:30,603 --> 00:04:32,071
But the boy isn't a Choi.

129
00:04:32,805 --> 00:04:34,307
Well, it's a nickname, so…

130
00:04:34,374 --> 00:04:36,576
-Right. He's a Kim.
-He's not a Choi.

131
00:04:36,643 --> 00:04:38,945
-He's a Kim.
-You're right.

132
00:04:39,012 --> 00:04:43,349
What if he grows up and says,
"Grandpa, I want to be a chef"?

133
00:04:43,416 --> 00:04:44,384
What would you do?

134
00:04:44,450 --> 00:04:46,119
I'll have to talk to him.

135
00:04:46,185 --> 00:04:47,420
"Tani."

136
00:04:47,487 --> 00:04:49,122
"A man who's as tall as you

137
00:04:49,188 --> 00:04:50,923
should not start cooking."

138
00:04:50,990 --> 00:04:53,026
"Play baseball," is what I'd say.

139
00:04:53,092 --> 00:04:54,661
Do you regret becoming a chef?

140
00:04:54,727 --> 00:04:56,462
-No.
-You're one of the best now.

141
00:04:56,529 --> 00:04:58,965
It's just like how Ji-tae said
he wanted to be a chef

142
00:04:59,032 --> 00:05:00,767
-in his next life.
-Yes, I really want to.

143
00:05:00,833 --> 00:05:02,402
If my son wanted to become a chef,

144
00:05:02,468 --> 00:05:04,370
I'd give him my support.

145
00:05:04,437 --> 00:05:06,105
-Yes, of course.
-Does your son like to cook?

146
00:05:06,172 --> 00:05:07,073
All right.

147
00:05:07,140 --> 00:05:08,641
-Starting today,
-Yes?

148
00:05:08,708 --> 00:05:10,910
-call me Choi Ji-tae.
-All of a sudden?

149
00:05:11,477 --> 00:05:12,645
HE KEEPS CALLING HIMSELF THAT…

150
00:05:12,712 --> 00:05:14,647
Anyway, good luck
with raising your grandson.

151
00:05:14,714 --> 00:05:15,982
ENOUGH OF THAT

152
00:05:16,049 --> 00:05:18,551
-"Good luck with that."
-The parents will do fine.

153
00:05:18,618 --> 00:05:20,186
Yes, leave it up to them.

154
00:05:20,253 --> 00:05:22,855
-You can be there to pamper him.
-You're the grandpa.

155
00:05:22,922 --> 00:05:25,858
Just give him your support
no matter what he wants to do.

156
00:05:25,925 --> 00:05:29,962
Min-jung, I heard you had a story
of Ji-tae's good deeds to share.

157
00:05:30,029 --> 00:05:32,965
He's very considerate of the entire staff,

158
00:05:33,032 --> 00:05:34,467
and one day, I even found

159
00:05:34,534 --> 00:05:36,669
my personal staff following him,

160
00:05:36,736 --> 00:05:38,871
because he always buys them
something delicious.

161
00:05:38,938 --> 00:05:42,608
He's loved by everyone on set.

162
00:05:42,675 --> 00:05:44,410
I'm so flattered.

163
00:05:44,477 --> 00:05:46,646
I hear you often host team dinners.

164
00:05:46,713 --> 00:05:48,981
Teamwork is everything, right?

165
00:05:49,048 --> 00:05:50,883
That's why I like having a drink
and a nice meal

166
00:05:50,950 --> 00:05:53,186
with the team
to make the workplace more amicable.

167
00:05:53,252 --> 00:05:54,987
But the production crew is usually huge

168
00:05:55,054 --> 00:05:57,857
-for a film production.
-Yes, it's a huge crew.

169
00:05:57,924 --> 00:06:00,760
I once gave them my credit card…

170
00:06:00,827 --> 00:06:02,128
and they really splurged.

171
00:06:04,163 --> 00:06:06,332
I usually spend between
three and five million won at a time

172
00:06:06,399 --> 00:06:08,301
-For one meal?
-Everyone.

173
00:06:08,368 --> 00:06:10,136
I received a tip from our production crew.

174
00:06:10,203 --> 00:06:11,904
Do you remember our dinner
at the end of last year?

175
00:06:12,472 --> 00:06:13,373
THE TEAM HAD DINNER

176
00:06:13,439 --> 00:06:15,408
-On that day, the tab…
-What is it?

177
00:06:15,475 --> 00:06:17,777
-…was paid in whole…
-Yes, right.

178
00:06:17,844 --> 00:06:20,480
…by Choi Hyun-suk,

179
00:06:21,114 --> 00:06:23,516
and he demanded that we mention it on air.

180
00:06:23,583 --> 00:06:25,017
FLAUNTING

181
00:06:25,351 --> 00:06:26,753
FLOPS OVER

182
00:06:26,819 --> 00:06:29,288
Should I not have
mentioned the latter part?

183
00:06:29,355 --> 00:06:31,557
-Chef Hyun-suk…
-That was so nice of him.

184
00:06:31,624 --> 00:06:34,060
CHOI JI-TAE PAYS FOR EVERYTHING

185
00:06:34,127 --> 00:06:36,028
-Thank you!
-He wanted us to mention it.

186
00:06:36,095 --> 00:06:38,498
-I had a lot on that day.
-It was a lot.

187
00:06:38,564 --> 00:06:40,533
But someone else did something nice.

188
00:06:40,600 --> 00:06:42,301
I was going to pay for everything,

189
00:06:42,368 --> 00:06:43,870
but someone had paid

190
00:06:43,936 --> 00:06:48,141
-a million won previously, like a deposit.
-Who was it?

191
00:06:48,207 --> 00:06:50,376
-It was Jung-hwan.
-My gosh.

192
00:06:50,843 --> 00:06:52,178
APPLAUDING AUTOMATICALLY

193
00:06:52,245 --> 00:06:54,046
-That's even cooler.
-So he paid the rest

194
00:06:54,113 --> 00:06:55,815
-excluding the million won.
-Is that it?

195
00:06:55,882 --> 00:06:58,050
-It couldn't have been much.
-You can't do that.

196
00:06:58,117 --> 00:06:59,852
-We had a team dinner before, right?
-Yes.

197
00:06:59,919 --> 00:07:00,920
I picked up the tab then,

198
00:07:00,987 --> 00:07:05,191
but some crew members couldn't come,
so I left a million won for them to eat.

199
00:07:05,258 --> 00:07:06,959
-Wow.
-And you used that?

200
00:07:07,026 --> 00:07:08,528
Give it up for Jung-hwan!

201
00:07:09,095 --> 00:07:11,164
YOU'RE THE BEST, JUNG-HWAN

202
00:07:11,898 --> 00:07:13,232
BITTER…

203
00:07:13,299 --> 00:07:14,367
That means he paid.

204
00:07:14,434 --> 00:07:16,803
-I have the receipt, actually.
-You do?

205
00:07:16,869 --> 00:07:17,970
-How much?
-I'm dying to know.

206
00:07:18,037 --> 00:07:20,206
Chef Hyun-suk paid a total of 480,000 won.

207
00:07:20,273 --> 00:07:21,174
Really?

208
00:07:21,240 --> 00:07:22,875
-That's a lot.
-I thought it was 4.8 million won.

209
00:07:23,443 --> 00:07:24,544
ABOUT 10% OF WHAT JI-TAE PAID

210
00:07:24,610 --> 00:07:27,480
I'll deposit a million won
as I head home today.

211
00:07:28,281 --> 00:07:29,615
-No.
-We're just joking.

212
00:07:29,682 --> 00:07:32,685
-Just give that to me.
-That's right.

213
00:07:32,752 --> 00:07:33,719
True.

214
00:07:33,786 --> 00:07:36,222
You must give it to me,
and then I can treat the staff members.

215
00:07:36,289 --> 00:07:38,591
-That's right.
-That's the right answer.

216
00:07:38,658 --> 00:07:40,460
I'll pay you via the money transfer app.

217
00:07:40,526 --> 00:07:41,794
HAPPY NOW?

218
00:07:41,861 --> 00:07:44,931
-Send it to me.
-Come on.

219
00:07:46,332 --> 00:07:47,967
-One second. Sorry.
-He's serious?

220
00:07:48,034 --> 00:07:49,435
He's going to send it now.

221
00:07:49,502 --> 00:07:51,437
You don't use that app over the phone.

222
00:07:51,504 --> 00:07:53,973
Why would you call to use an app?

223
00:07:54,040 --> 00:07:57,210
-You used my money!
-That's enough.

224
00:07:57,276 --> 00:07:59,345
What will our guests think?

225
00:07:59,412 --> 00:08:01,447
-We have guests here!
-Settle down!

226
00:08:01,514 --> 00:08:03,850
It's not like a hotel deposit.
Why do you need it back?

227
00:08:03,916 --> 00:08:05,685
I'm sorry.

228
00:08:05,751 --> 00:08:07,119
They usually aren't like this.

229
00:08:07,186 --> 00:08:09,355
CHAOS

230
00:08:10,523 --> 00:08:12,859
CRYING FIT OF LAUGHTER

231
00:08:12,925 --> 00:08:15,061
They keep having to see this.

232
00:08:15,127 --> 00:08:17,630
-We're sorry.
-It's all right.

233
00:08:17,697 --> 00:08:19,899
-Apologize to them.
-I'm sorry.

234
00:08:20,399 --> 00:08:21,434
EVERYONE GETS ALONG HERE

235
00:08:21,501 --> 00:08:23,569
As you all know very well,

236
00:08:23,636 --> 00:08:25,805
he's been married to actress Kim Hyo-jin

237
00:08:25,872 --> 00:08:29,809
<i>-for the past 15 years.</i>
<i>-It's already been 15 years?</i>

238
00:08:29,876 --> 00:08:33,779
Ji-tae still counts the days
since they began dating,

239
00:08:33,846 --> 00:08:36,649
so he knows exactly how many days
they've been together.

240
00:08:36,716 --> 00:08:38,484
-Really?
-How many days has it been

241
00:08:38,551 --> 00:08:41,087
since you two began dating?

242
00:08:41,153 --> 00:08:42,688
It's been 6,961 days.

243
00:08:42,755 --> 00:08:43,723
ANSWERS IMMEDIATELY

244
00:08:43,789 --> 00:08:45,224
-It's been 6,961 days?
-Yes.

245
00:08:45,291 --> 00:08:47,727
I have the date set on my phone.

246
00:08:47,793 --> 00:08:49,028
-That's how I know.
-The fact that you do

247
00:08:49,095 --> 00:08:51,297
-is so sweet.
-Did you do that yourself?

248
00:08:51,364 --> 00:08:53,533
-Meet a guy like him.
-I need a guy like him.

249
00:08:53,599 --> 00:08:54,834
Do you have an idea?

250
00:08:54,901 --> 00:08:56,569
He says every single day

251
00:08:56,636 --> 00:08:58,371
is like the first day we met.

252
00:08:58,638 --> 00:09:00,106
MY GOSH

253
00:09:00,172 --> 00:09:02,008
Those aren't my words.

254
00:09:02,074 --> 00:09:03,943
My husband is the one that says that.

255
00:09:04,443 --> 00:09:07,713
Because I'm someone
with many different characters,

256
00:09:07,780 --> 00:09:10,249
so there are days
when I'm soft-spoken, and…

257
00:09:11,050 --> 00:09:13,019
AN ALTERNATE MEANING

258
00:09:13,085 --> 00:09:14,754
He says I make him nervous.

259
00:09:14,820 --> 00:09:17,056
THE KIND OF CHARM THAT KEEPS HIM ON EDGE

260
00:09:17,123 --> 00:09:19,158
That's why he keeps trembling his legs
when he eats.

261
00:09:19,225 --> 00:09:21,561
-Yes, that's why.
-He gets nervous.

262
00:09:21,627 --> 00:09:22,595
Well,

263
00:09:22,662 --> 00:09:25,464
previously, we took a look
at what Min-jung keeps in her fridge.

264
00:09:25,531 --> 00:09:26,899
-Fridge!
-Fridge!

265
00:09:26,966 --> 00:09:27,833
-That's a lot.
-It's full.

266
00:09:28,134 --> 00:09:30,503
AWESOME INGREDIENTS
AS IF THEY WERE IN PARADISE

267
00:09:31,070 --> 00:09:32,572
A WELL-STOCKED FRIDGE

268
00:09:32,638 --> 00:09:35,141
But look at the size of Ji-tae's fridge.

269
00:09:35,207 --> 00:09:38,077
-What?
-It's rather small in comparison.

270
00:09:38,544 --> 00:09:41,414
IT'S UNUSUALLY SMALL

271
00:09:41,480 --> 00:09:42,949
Wait, wasn't Joo Woo-jae's fridge…

272
00:09:43,015 --> 00:09:45,318
You may have to face a fridge

273
00:09:45,384 --> 00:09:48,187
that'll whip you good
this early in the year.

274
00:09:48,254 --> 00:09:49,989
It's the new year,
so we should pull it together.

275
00:09:50,056 --> 00:09:52,325
He could've brought that
to give you a tough time.

276
00:09:52,391 --> 00:09:54,694
Is there a reason why you use a small one?

277
00:09:54,760 --> 00:09:56,629
It's not the one at home, actually.

278
00:09:56,696 --> 00:09:58,998
It's from my office at the university.

279
00:09:59,065 --> 00:10:01,601
-That sounds dangerous.
-We can't work with that.

280
00:10:01,667 --> 00:10:03,002
On Mondays,

281
00:10:03,069 --> 00:10:05,504
I work 9 a.m. to 9 p.m.,
a total of 12 hours,

282
00:10:05,571 --> 00:10:07,740
and I don't get a proper break
in the middle.

283
00:10:07,807 --> 00:10:10,876
There are three four-hour classes
in a row.

284
00:10:10,943 --> 00:10:13,279
-Twelve hours.
-Then you should eat during short breaks.

285
00:10:13,346 --> 00:10:15,514
Yes, I only have 15 minutes.

286
00:10:15,581 --> 00:10:17,550
-Just 15 minutes?
-In 15 minutes?

287
00:10:17,617 --> 00:10:19,385
-Like <i>Chef & My Fridge.</i>
-In that case,

288
00:10:19,452 --> 00:10:20,953
when do you get off on weekdays?

289
00:10:21,020 --> 00:10:23,889
I have a place in both Songdo and Seoul.

290
00:10:23,956 --> 00:10:27,893
I tend to stay in Seoul
when I have a lot of work to do.

291
00:10:27,960 --> 00:10:29,829
So you're in the office
during the weekdays?

292
00:10:29,895 --> 00:10:32,298
Yes, from Monday to Friday,
I'm in my office.

293
00:10:32,365 --> 00:10:35,835
-So only on weekends?
-Yes, I go home and see my kids.

294
00:10:35,901 --> 00:10:37,169
You're a weekend couple.

295
00:10:37,236 --> 00:10:41,040
He uses this fridge five days a week,
so it seems more appropriate for the show.

296
00:10:41,107 --> 00:10:43,609
But professors only keep
things like beverages

297
00:10:44,176 --> 00:10:46,178
-in the fridge in their offices.
-Perhaps some juice.

298
00:10:46,245 --> 00:10:48,114
-Maybe sponge cake or bread.
-Mostly beverages.

299
00:10:48,180 --> 00:10:50,282
-Exactly.
-Maybe some fruit.

300
00:10:50,349 --> 00:10:52,518
In that case, how will they cook?

301
00:10:52,585 --> 00:10:54,186
Well, we manage.

302
00:10:54,253 --> 00:10:55,321
-We must.
-We do it.

303
00:10:55,388 --> 00:10:57,056
-Why don't we take a look?
-Let's do that.

304
00:10:57,123 --> 00:10:59,058
Professor Yoo.

305
00:10:59,125 --> 00:11:03,295
What kind of ingredients
does Professor Yoo keep in his fridge?

306
00:11:03,362 --> 00:11:04,797
-We present his fridge!
-Fridge!

307
00:11:05,364 --> 00:11:08,534
-He does have some stuff.
-He has some ingredients.

308
00:11:08,601 --> 00:11:10,336
-We present his fridge!
-Fridge!

309
00:11:11,737 --> 00:11:14,306
-He does have some stuff.
-He has some ingredients.

310
00:11:14,373 --> 00:11:16,308
-That's a lot.
-He has some stuff.

311
00:11:16,375 --> 00:11:18,411
I thought he'd only have beverages.

312
00:11:18,477 --> 00:11:20,312
-All right. Take a look.
-He has tofu.

313
00:11:20,379 --> 00:11:22,348
I thought it'd be just lines of beverages,

314
00:11:22,415 --> 00:11:25,051
-but he has some food here.
-He has tomato sauce.

315
00:11:25,117 --> 00:11:27,586
The top shelf. What's this?

316
00:11:27,653 --> 00:11:30,189
-Healthy diet… Protein Meal.
-Goat's milk.

317
00:11:30,256 --> 00:11:32,024
-What's this?
-Protein? For his workouts?

318
00:11:32,091 --> 00:11:34,460
During the production of <i>Vigilante,</i>

319
00:11:34,527 --> 00:11:39,398
<i>I had to take 800 g of carbs</i>
<i>and protein every single day.</i>

320
00:11:39,465 --> 00:11:41,567
He was this big on the screen.

321
00:11:41,634 --> 00:11:44,403
But it was very difficult to eat
as actual food,

322
00:11:44,470 --> 00:11:45,471
so I used powder.

323
00:11:45,538 --> 00:11:47,973
I see. This is powder.

324
00:11:48,040 --> 00:11:49,341
You have lots of powders.

325
00:11:49,408 --> 00:11:51,177
I see organic potato powder,

326
00:11:51,243 --> 00:11:52,311
turmeric powder,

327
00:11:52,378 --> 00:11:54,280
-and powdered broccoli.
-Yes.

328
00:11:54,346 --> 00:11:55,448
-All powders.
-That's for my immunity.

329
00:11:55,514 --> 00:11:56,816
-They are.
-All powders.

330
00:11:56,882 --> 00:11:58,217
He only keeps powder.

331
00:11:58,284 --> 00:11:59,752
-Cooking with powder.
-Yes.

332
00:11:59,819 --> 00:12:01,420
Do you throw everything in and mix it?

333
00:12:01,487 --> 00:12:02,822
I just like to drink it.

334
00:12:02,888 --> 00:12:04,156
DRINKING

335
00:12:04,223 --> 00:12:06,025
-With these?
-With soy milk.

336
00:12:06,092 --> 00:12:08,027
I see. He mixes them with soy milk.

337
00:12:08,094 --> 00:12:10,129
I see some carrot juice too.

338
00:12:10,196 --> 00:12:11,931
It's either powder or juice.

339
00:12:12,364 --> 00:12:14,266
INGREDIENT EMERGENCY

340
00:12:14,333 --> 00:12:16,936
Do you drink your meals
because it's hard to cook there?

341
00:12:17,002 --> 00:12:18,771
I heat it up in the microwave.

342
00:12:18,838 --> 00:12:20,306
-The microwave.
-What's this?

343
00:12:20,372 --> 00:12:23,909
-But I see some sauces here.
-Right? That's not for juice.

344
00:12:23,976 --> 00:12:25,377
It's bacon and cream sauce.

345
00:12:25,444 --> 00:12:27,513
They go with chicken breast.

346
00:12:28,080 --> 00:12:29,448
Because they get dry.

347
00:12:29,515 --> 00:12:30,649
They get quite dry.

348
00:12:30,716 --> 00:12:32,351
-He can't eat it as is.
-It's the sauce.

349
00:12:32,418 --> 00:12:34,653
I found something like this.

350
00:12:34,720 --> 00:12:39,058
He has disposable chopsticks too.

351
00:12:39,792 --> 00:12:40,960
That happens.

352
00:12:41,026 --> 00:12:42,294
-It's in the fridge.
-It happens.

353
00:12:42,361 --> 00:12:44,330
I get it. These end up in the fridge.

354
00:12:44,396 --> 00:12:46,599
-You have nowhere else to keep them.
-Right.

355
00:12:46,665 --> 00:12:48,968
And down here, he has tofu.

356
00:12:49,034 --> 00:12:51,303
It's my chicken breast substitute.

357
00:12:51,370 --> 00:12:52,905
-Right. Protein.
-And tofu noodles?

358
00:12:52,972 --> 00:12:55,608
-I mix it with the sauce.
-Do you mix it?

359
00:12:55,674 --> 00:12:57,209
-You mix it with the sauce.
-I do.

360
00:12:57,276 --> 00:12:58,744
Those are substitutes for noodles.

361
00:12:58,811 --> 00:13:00,379
My fridge is too poorly stocked.

362
00:13:00,446 --> 00:13:01,714
Do you eat it cold?

363
00:13:01,781 --> 00:13:03,516
I warm it up in the microwave.

364
00:13:03,582 --> 00:13:05,117
Goodness. The microwave.

365
00:13:05,184 --> 00:13:07,486
-I've never seen…
-This is another powder.

366
00:13:07,553 --> 00:13:09,288
-That counts as powder?
-Seaweed flakes.

367
00:13:09,355 --> 00:13:12,258
-He has lots of powdered food.
-He does.

368
00:13:12,324 --> 00:13:14,426
He has some kimchi.

369
00:13:14,493 --> 00:13:15,928
-Stir-fried kimchi.
-Stir-fried kimchi.

370
00:13:15,995 --> 00:13:18,964
-Kimchi<i>-jjigae</i> is my favorite food.
-Kimchi stew.

371
00:13:19,031 --> 00:13:20,399
I see.

372
00:13:20,466 --> 00:13:22,668
Do you eat kimchi<i>-jjigae</i> at home
on the weekends?

373
00:13:22,735 --> 00:13:24,703
Yes, my wife makes it for me.

374
00:13:24,970 --> 00:13:25,905
LOVING HER HUBBY FOR 6,961 DAYS

375
00:13:25,971 --> 00:13:28,474
-She knows it's your favorite.
-She makes it for dinner.

376
00:13:28,541 --> 00:13:30,609
-So that's Kim Hyo-jin's kimchi<i>-jjigae.</i>
-Yes.

377
00:13:30,676 --> 00:13:32,778
What's the recipe like?

378
00:13:32,845 --> 00:13:37,116
Actually, my wife is a vegetarian,

379
00:13:37,183 --> 00:13:39,318
so she dreads even touching meat.

380
00:13:39,385 --> 00:13:40,686
IT'S TOUGH FOR HER

381
00:13:40,753 --> 00:13:44,924
But when I return home,
she makes kimchi<i>-jjigae</i> with pork,

382
00:13:44,990 --> 00:13:46,959
-which is purely for my sake.
-It must be.

383
00:13:47,026 --> 00:13:48,093
It is.

384
00:13:48,160 --> 00:13:51,530
However, she can't taste it
after she finishes making it,

385
00:13:51,597 --> 00:13:52,698
so that's up to me.

386
00:13:52,765 --> 00:13:54,099
ENJOYING THE DISH IS UP TO ME

387
00:13:54,166 --> 00:13:55,668
It's either hit or miss.

388
00:13:55,734 --> 00:13:58,938
But I think I mostly enjoyed it.

389
00:13:59,638 --> 00:14:01,207
-Greens?
-Wait.

390
00:14:01,273 --> 00:14:03,442
We found some greens
used to make veggie wraps.

391
00:14:03,509 --> 00:14:05,544
Do you grill meat in the office?

392
00:14:05,611 --> 00:14:07,780
I have to have vegetables,

393
00:14:07,847 --> 00:14:09,281
but salad is too expensive.

394
00:14:09,348 --> 00:14:11,617
-You're right.
-It's between 10,000 won and 12,000 won.

395
00:14:11,684 --> 00:14:13,586
-But that's only 3,800 won.
-That's true.

396
00:14:14,653 --> 00:14:16,222
You aren't doing that badly though.

397
00:14:16,689 --> 00:14:19,258
THE THRIFTY PROFESSOR YOO

398
00:14:19,325 --> 00:14:20,693
I mean, he's doing well.

399
00:14:20,759 --> 00:14:23,495
The problem
isn't if I'm doing well or badly.

400
00:14:23,562 --> 00:14:25,331
We must be wise with money.

401
00:14:25,397 --> 00:14:28,167
-Yes, we must be.
-I should learn from him.

402
00:14:28,234 --> 00:14:30,369
He's willing to spend
five million won on the crew,

403
00:14:30,436 --> 00:14:32,838
-but he eats cheaper veggies.
-How cool.

404
00:14:32,905 --> 00:14:34,673
-That's so cool.
-You're right.

405
00:14:34,740 --> 00:14:36,809
THE COOL PROFESSOR YOO

406
00:14:36,876 --> 00:14:38,143
Do you eat just the greens?

407
00:14:38,210 --> 00:14:40,446
-I wrap chicken breast with it.
-As veggie wraps.

408
00:14:40,512 --> 00:14:44,450
Every sauce and other ingredients exist
to help him eat his chicken breast.

409
00:14:44,516 --> 00:14:45,985
-I can't help it.
-It's too dry as is.

410
00:14:46,051 --> 00:14:47,219
-He can't help it.
-It sounds tough.

411
00:14:47,286 --> 00:14:49,722
-He sprinkles sauce over the chicken.
-Yes.

412
00:14:49,788 --> 00:14:51,523
What's down here? Thistle!

413
00:14:51,590 --> 00:14:53,158
These are all microwaveable.

414
00:14:53,225 --> 00:14:54,326
Thistle rice.

415
00:14:54,393 --> 00:14:55,394
-Do you like these?
-When…

416
00:14:55,461 --> 00:14:58,764
Yes, I have to eat carbs
before I work out,

417
00:14:58,831 --> 00:15:01,667
and thistle rice seems to be the best.

418
00:15:01,734 --> 00:15:02,635
-It's the best.
-It's good.

419
00:15:02,701 --> 00:15:04,069
I top it with seaweed flakes.

420
00:15:04,136 --> 00:15:06,138
POWDER WITH EVERYTHING

421
00:15:06,205 --> 00:15:07,973
He keeps chicken breast here.

422
00:15:08,040 --> 00:15:10,142
Professor Yoo eats
a whole lot of chicken breast.

423
00:15:11,443 --> 00:15:12,444
How many are there?

424
00:15:12,511 --> 00:15:15,581
-He has four bags of these.
-I found another one!

425
00:15:15,648 --> 00:15:16,482
Another one.

426
00:15:16,548 --> 00:15:18,017
A PILE OF CHICKEN BREAST

427
00:15:18,083 --> 00:15:21,587
He eats these as veggie wraps
and with those sauces.

428
00:15:21,654 --> 00:15:23,422
Gosh. He must've been so sick of it.

429
00:15:23,489 --> 00:15:25,257
-He must microwave these.
-Yes.

430
00:15:25,324 --> 00:15:27,860
What's the craziest thing
you've microwaved?

431
00:15:28,427 --> 00:15:29,828
Mackerel.

432
00:15:29,895 --> 00:15:31,130
-Mackerel?
-Mackerel in a microwave?

433
00:15:31,196 --> 00:15:32,564
-Raw ones?
-Doesn't it smell?

434
00:15:32,631 --> 00:15:35,701
-No, there are pre-packaged ones.
-The pre-made ones.

435
00:15:35,768 --> 00:15:39,505
As we speak, we just found
a video of him cooking the mackerel.

436
00:15:39,571 --> 00:15:40,406
Let's take a look.

437
00:15:40,472 --> 00:15:43,409
-Here's how I take protein with mackerel.
-That's my studio.

438
00:15:43,475 --> 00:15:44,543
That's Professor Yoo.

439
00:15:44,610 --> 00:15:46,512
-Now, a mackerel.
<i>-That's the mackerel.</i>

440
00:15:46,578 --> 00:15:48,080
-It's raw?
-The raw one?

441
00:15:48,147 --> 00:15:49,214
-It's raw?
-It'll smell.

442
00:15:49,281 --> 00:15:50,316
You can't do that.

443
00:15:50,382 --> 00:15:51,650
-Doesn't it get fishy?
-It's raw?

444
00:15:51,717 --> 00:15:53,452
-It's raw, not ready-to-eat?
-Raw mackerel?

445
00:15:53,519 --> 00:15:54,586
Let's keep watching.

446
00:15:54,653 --> 00:15:55,721
ONE MACKEREL

447
00:15:55,788 --> 00:15:57,022
He's serious.

448
00:15:57,089 --> 00:15:58,157
A LUMP OF ASSORTED SEAFOOD

449
00:15:58,223 --> 00:16:00,159
<i>-Assorted seafood. Broccoli.</i>
<i>-Sorry?</i>

450
00:16:00,225 --> 00:16:01,193
<i>-Right. Broccoli.</i>
<i>-That's…</i>

451
00:16:01,260 --> 00:16:03,262
<i>-Pasta sauce?</i>
<i>-Just like that.</i>

452
00:16:03,329 --> 00:16:04,596
READY TO GO

453
00:16:04,863 --> 00:16:06,065
JEEZ…

454
00:16:06,131 --> 00:16:07,967
That's how I steam everything.

455
00:16:08,033 --> 00:16:09,435
<i>-Without using a stove.</i>
<i>-No.</i>

456
00:16:09,501 --> 00:16:10,703
FINISHED IN THE MICROWAVE

457
00:16:10,769 --> 00:16:12,338
It turns out like that.

458
00:16:13,038 --> 00:16:15,741
-It doesn't look so bad.
-Yes, it could be good.

459
00:16:16,075 --> 00:16:17,376
YUM

460
00:16:17,443 --> 00:16:19,144
YUM YUM

461
00:16:19,411 --> 00:16:20,579
FINISHED

462
00:16:20,646 --> 00:16:22,014
THAT WAS A GOOD MEAL

463
00:16:22,081 --> 00:16:25,184
That kind of preparation
will make it much more fishy.

464
00:16:25,250 --> 00:16:26,952
That's why I use intense sauce.

465
00:16:27,019 --> 00:16:28,687
He covers up the smell.

466
00:16:28,754 --> 00:16:31,290
-That was why you poured in tomato sauce.
-Yes.

467
00:16:31,357 --> 00:16:32,925
At times, I use turmeric powder.

468
00:16:32,992 --> 00:16:35,060
-Turmeric powder?
-Right.

469
00:16:35,127 --> 00:16:36,628
-Turmeric powder.
-He had his own technique.

470
00:16:36,695 --> 00:16:38,664
-Turmeric powder.
-That was what it was for.

471
00:16:38,731 --> 00:16:40,299
-I wondered why he had it.
-That was why.

472
00:16:40,366 --> 00:16:42,334
And the next drawer.

473
00:16:42,568 --> 00:16:45,070
ASSORTMENT OF FROZEN VEGETABLES

474
00:16:45,137 --> 00:16:48,607
I have to eat vegetables,
but it's tough to do that.

475
00:16:48,674 --> 00:16:51,710
-You can't use fire.
-Do you microwave those too?

476
00:16:51,777 --> 00:16:53,012
-I do.
-He can stick those in.

477
00:16:53,078 --> 00:16:53,912
HAHAHAHAHA

478
00:16:54,446 --> 00:16:56,382
Some seafood mix.

479
00:16:56,448 --> 00:16:59,084
-Can you microwave this too?
-What's that?

480
00:16:59,151 --> 00:17:01,286
-It's…
-It's <i>dongtae-tang</i>, frozen pollack stew.

481
00:17:01,353 --> 00:17:04,089
I had to meet the minimum amount

482
00:17:04,156 --> 00:17:06,458
-of 40,000 won on the delivery app.
-He got whatever.

483
00:17:06,525 --> 00:17:09,328
I got that by mistake,
so I thought of making it at home.

484
00:17:09,395 --> 00:17:12,564
-But it wasn't for you to eat there.
-It was to fill up your cart.

485
00:17:12,631 --> 00:17:15,334
-We'll make good use of that today.
-We will.

486
00:17:15,401 --> 00:17:16,835
This is something he has to boil.

487
00:17:16,902 --> 00:17:19,104
-There's dumplings too.
-We can use those.

488
00:17:19,171 --> 00:17:22,908
-And microwaveable hamburger steak.
-I can microwave that.

489
00:17:22,975 --> 00:17:24,343
I have to get my hands on that.

490
00:17:24,410 --> 00:17:26,612
You'll have to make good use of powders.

491
00:17:26,678 --> 00:17:27,613
Powder or frozen food.

492
00:17:27,679 --> 00:17:29,481
Powder or frozen food?

493
00:17:29,548 --> 00:17:32,718
He's busy, so he's been filling himself up
using powders.

494
00:17:32,785 --> 00:17:35,354
I wonder what his assignments will be.

495
00:17:35,421 --> 00:17:37,256
That was all for Ji-tae's fridge.

496
00:17:37,322 --> 00:17:39,224
DONE CHECKING OUT HIS FRIDGE

497
00:17:39,825 --> 00:17:41,727
Now, for the first time on the show,

498
00:17:41,794 --> 00:17:45,464
we looked through a fridge
from a professor's office.

499
00:17:45,531 --> 00:17:48,734
But what's important
is the professor's order.

500
00:17:48,801 --> 00:17:50,769
I'm sure he won't ask for something

501
00:17:50,836 --> 00:17:52,971
too difficult to make
with what he has in the fridge.

502
00:17:53,038 --> 00:17:55,607
All right, then. Our dear Professor Yoo.

503
00:17:55,674 --> 00:17:57,609
What is the kind of meal he wants?

504
00:17:57,676 --> 00:17:59,578
Let's find out his orders.

505
00:17:59,645 --> 00:18:00,512
Show us!

506
00:18:00,579 --> 00:18:02,147
-A full-course meal?
-What does he want?

507
00:18:02,214 --> 00:18:03,715
I doubt it'll be a course meal.

508
00:18:03,782 --> 00:18:05,384
COOK WITHOUT USING FIRE (15 MINUTES)

509
00:18:05,451 --> 00:18:06,718
What's that?

510
00:18:06,785 --> 00:18:07,886
EVEN THE FONT IS DIFFERENT…

511
00:18:07,953 --> 00:18:08,987
-That font.
-What's that font?

512
00:18:09,054 --> 00:18:11,356
ARE WE ABOUT TO TAKE A TEST?

513
00:18:11,423 --> 00:18:13,459
-It's the BatangChe font.
-It's so serious.

514
00:18:13,525 --> 00:18:15,627
-It's a 15-point question.
-That's so witty.

515
00:18:15,694 --> 00:18:18,030
I literally have 15 minutes

516
00:18:18,097 --> 00:18:22,668
to make something and gulp it down
before I return to the lecture hall.

517
00:18:22,734 --> 00:18:24,103
So in any way without using the stove?

518
00:18:24,169 --> 00:18:26,071
I'm not allowed to use fire
as my heat source.

519
00:18:26,138 --> 00:18:28,474
-He can't because it's hazardous.
-Anything but the stove.

520
00:18:28,540 --> 00:18:29,541
-That's hard.
-Okay.

521
00:18:29,608 --> 00:18:31,877
What's the next order from the professor?

522
00:18:31,944 --> 00:18:34,246
What's his next assignment?

523
00:18:35,080 --> 00:18:36,949
-Make a Healthy Dish,
-Make a Healthy Dish,

524
00:18:37,015 --> 00:18:39,785
-But Use Convenience Food.
-But Use Convenience Food.

525
00:18:39,852 --> 00:18:42,121
HAHAHAHAHA

526
00:18:42,187 --> 00:18:43,288
-That's cruel.
-They don't line up.

527
00:18:43,355 --> 00:18:45,724
A healthy dish using convenience food?

528
00:18:45,791 --> 00:18:49,061
Come up with a healthy dish
using convenience food.

529
00:18:49,128 --> 00:18:51,697
I have no choice
but to resort to convenience food,

530
00:18:51,763 --> 00:18:53,932
but I still want to live a healthy life.

531
00:18:53,999 --> 00:18:55,434
-I look forward to it.
-That's true.

532
00:18:55,501 --> 00:18:58,403
What he's asking us to do

533
00:18:58,470 --> 00:19:00,973
is like alchemy for chefs.

534
00:19:01,039 --> 00:19:02,441
-That's so right.
-Alchemy.

535
00:19:02,508 --> 00:19:06,145
Convenience foods are already
so far from healthiness,

536
00:19:06,211 --> 00:19:07,679
but we must make them healthy.

537
00:19:07,746 --> 00:19:08,981
-I'm so glad.
-The four of you,

538
00:19:09,047 --> 00:19:11,650
the remaining four chefs,
will make the decision.

539
00:19:11,717 --> 00:19:13,585
-That's great.
-Microwaving food…

540
00:19:13,652 --> 00:19:16,088
-I kind of want to join.
-…isn't a healthy way to cook.

541
00:19:16,155 --> 00:19:19,491
-She wants to join.
-I suddenly want to take on the challenge.

542
00:19:19,558 --> 00:19:21,727
If you don't choose soon,
Min-jung will take your place.

543
00:19:22,995 --> 00:19:25,430
-Come on. Save our show's face.
-Please.

544
00:19:25,497 --> 00:19:27,966
The quicker you choose,
the more advantageous you will be.

545
00:19:28,367 --> 00:19:29,701
DODGING THE PROFESSOR'S EYES…

546
00:19:29,768 --> 00:19:32,571
Who wants to choose first
among the three over there?

547
00:19:32,638 --> 00:19:34,806
-The young 'uns.
-The young 'uns?

548
00:19:34,873 --> 00:19:36,408
-I'll go.
-Chef Eun-yeong?

549
00:19:36,475 --> 00:19:37,476
-Yes.
-Yes, go ahead.

550
00:19:37,543 --> 00:19:40,078
I'll go for the second one
and make a healthy dish.

551
00:19:40,145 --> 00:19:42,381
The healthy dish using convenience food.

552
00:19:42,447 --> 00:19:44,416
As a longtime fan of Ji-tae's,

553
00:19:44,483 --> 00:19:48,020
I want to make him something healthy
despite the convenience foods he has.

554
00:19:49,321 --> 00:19:51,423
-Thank you.
-She's doing it as a fan.

555
00:19:51,490 --> 00:19:53,058
-Then I'll have to go.
-Yes?

556
00:19:53,725 --> 00:19:55,727
I'll make a healthy dish too.

557
00:19:55,794 --> 00:19:58,363
That was quick. Nam-no just jumped in.

558
00:19:58,430 --> 00:20:00,999
Chef Eun-yeong took second place
in the previous season,

559
00:20:01,066 --> 00:20:02,668
and she's been getting an attitude.

560
00:20:04,002 --> 00:20:07,706
I'll give her a taste of defeat
as we open up the new year.

561
00:20:07,773 --> 00:20:09,374
This means

562
00:20:09,441 --> 00:20:12,077
the rest is automatic for these two,
who'll cook without fire.

563
00:20:12,144 --> 00:20:13,245
They told us to jump in.

564
00:20:13,312 --> 00:20:15,747
Choi Hyun-suk versus Kwon Sung-jun.

565
00:20:15,814 --> 00:20:17,316
-You're right.
-Good luck.

566
00:20:17,382 --> 00:20:18,617
We're sorry about that.

567
00:20:18,684 --> 00:20:19,685
-I wish
-You're usually quick.

568
00:20:19,751 --> 00:20:21,053
to recommend Rhee Min-jung.

569
00:20:21,119 --> 00:20:23,188
CHOI HYUN-SUK VS. RHEE MIN-JUNG(?)

570
00:20:23,255 --> 00:20:25,824
She was seriously wondering
what she would make.

571
00:20:25,891 --> 00:20:27,960
I'm dying to know how that will turn out.

572
00:20:28,026 --> 00:20:30,562
-What do I do?
-I've been thinking of those powders,

573
00:20:30,629 --> 00:20:32,898
and it seemed quite difficult.

574
00:20:32,965 --> 00:20:36,068
All right. Time to cook for Ji-tae.

575
00:20:36,134 --> 00:20:40,439
Chef Hyun-suk and Sung-jun
will begin cooking without using fire!

576
00:20:40,505 --> 00:20:44,042
A COOKING SHOW WITHOUT FIRE
IS COMING RIGHT UP

577
00:20:44,109 --> 00:20:48,513
<i>This is the first cook-off</i>
<i>with ingredients from Ji-tae's fridge.</i>

578
00:20:48,580 --> 00:20:50,582
The expectant grandfather,

579
00:20:50,649 --> 00:20:53,485
the old boy of <i>Chef & My Fridge,</i>
Chef Choi Hyun-suk,

580
00:20:53,552 --> 00:20:55,320
is up against the youngest
among the young'uns,

581
00:20:55,387 --> 00:20:59,024
the young boy of Chef & My Fridge,
Chef Kwon Sung-jun.

582
00:20:59,091 --> 00:21:00,759
Age is just a number,

583
00:21:00,826 --> 00:21:02,928
but there is something called
the aging curve.

584
00:21:02,995 --> 00:21:05,330
-Yes, and that's inevitable.
-Yes.

585
00:21:05,397 --> 00:21:06,598
That's just aging.

586
00:21:06,665 --> 00:21:09,368
-It impacts one of these two.
-Right.

587
00:21:09,434 --> 00:21:12,537
And I thought I'd bring it up
because he's about to be a grandfather.

588
00:21:12,604 --> 00:21:15,707
Of course, fastballs are powerful,

589
00:21:15,774 --> 00:21:16,775
but curves

590
00:21:16,842 --> 00:21:19,544
are harder for the batters to hit.

591
00:21:19,611 --> 00:21:20,579
Don't you understand baseball?

592
00:21:20,646 --> 00:21:22,114
-What?
-That was random.

593
00:21:22,180 --> 00:21:24,883
-What now? What's he talking about?
-What are you getting at?

594
00:21:24,950 --> 00:21:27,619
-He has trouble with listening.
-What is he saying?

595
00:21:27,686 --> 00:21:29,821
He has hit the aging curve.

596
00:21:29,888 --> 00:21:32,190
-You've lost your eloquence too.
-How unfortunate.

597
00:21:32,257 --> 00:21:34,459
-He couldn't understand.
-He keeps losing it.

598
00:21:34,526 --> 00:21:36,662
He has no idea what he's trying to say.

599
00:21:36,728 --> 00:21:37,629
There's no conclusion.

600
00:21:37,696 --> 00:21:40,365
Gosh, I'm so sorry, Hyun-suk.

601
00:21:40,432 --> 00:21:42,668
When it comes to culinary arts,

602
00:21:42,734 --> 00:21:44,369
more years add more depth.

603
00:21:44,436 --> 00:21:45,737
I GOT WHAT'S CALLED DEPTH, KIDS!

604
00:21:45,804 --> 00:21:47,339
Need I say more?

605
00:21:47,406 --> 00:21:48,707
No, thank you.

606
00:21:48,774 --> 00:21:50,242
LOUD AND CLEAR

607
00:21:50,309 --> 00:21:53,078
I had to cut him off
while I had the chance.

608
00:21:53,145 --> 00:21:56,181
Despite the aging curve,
your flavor deepens like fermented sauces.

609
00:21:56,248 --> 00:21:57,783
He's like aged soy sauce.

610
00:21:57,849 --> 00:21:59,918
Aged soy sauce, Chef Hyun-suk.

611
00:21:59,985 --> 00:22:02,321
However, your assignment today

612
00:22:02,387 --> 00:22:04,022
is rather difficult.

613
00:22:04,089 --> 00:22:06,692
You have to cook without using the stove.

614
00:22:06,758 --> 00:22:10,395
I'm not sure if Sung-jun can handle
a challenge of this level.

615
00:22:10,462 --> 00:22:12,331
Honestly speaking, I never cook at home,

616
00:22:12,397 --> 00:22:14,800
so I microwave everything.

617
00:22:14,866 --> 00:22:16,768
-At home?
-I never use the stove.

618
00:22:16,835 --> 00:22:18,437
Actually, I even cook

619
00:22:18,503 --> 00:22:20,305
a bag of <i>ramyeon </i>in the microwave.

620
00:22:20,605 --> 00:22:21,707
HE FOUND A HOPEFUL ASPIRANT

621
00:22:21,773 --> 00:22:23,075
-Like they do in the army?
-Hence,

622
00:22:23,141 --> 00:22:25,844
-you can call me the microwave expert.
-I see.

623
00:22:25,911 --> 00:22:28,413
Also, I'll recreate the situation
in his office.

624
00:22:28,480 --> 00:22:29,881
You couldn't have a knife on campus,

625
00:22:29,948 --> 00:22:30,782
so I also won't use one.

626
00:22:30,849 --> 00:22:32,918
-Not even a knife?
-No knife, no fire.

627
00:22:32,984 --> 00:22:34,319
THE YOUNG BOY'S VIGOR

628
00:22:34,386 --> 00:22:35,587
Not even a knife?

629
00:22:35,654 --> 00:22:37,556
I won't use anything.
Well, I'll use scissors.

630
00:22:37,622 --> 00:22:39,257
-He'll use scissors.
-But scissors, yes.

631
00:22:39,324 --> 00:22:41,560
I'll make something
without using a knife or fire.

632
00:22:41,793 --> 00:22:43,528
A YOUNG MAN WITH SUCH VIGOR!
VIGOR: A

633
00:22:44,096 --> 00:22:46,164
But Chef Hyun-suk pulls out a knife.

634
00:22:46,231 --> 00:22:48,200
I SHALL SEAL MY KNIFE TOO!

635
00:22:48,266 --> 00:22:50,802
He put it in the opposite way.

636
00:22:50,869 --> 00:22:52,237
THE KNIFE WENT IN THE WRONG WAY…

637
00:22:52,304 --> 00:22:53,605
It went in the wrong way.

638
00:22:53,672 --> 00:22:55,340
SERIOUSLY?

639
00:22:55,407 --> 00:22:57,008
Why is he doing that?

640
00:22:57,075 --> 00:22:58,977
He put the knife away like a swordsman.

641
00:22:59,044 --> 00:23:00,879
Did you put it back in the sheath?

642
00:23:00,946 --> 00:23:03,615
-I did.
-That's who he is.

643
00:23:04,383 --> 00:23:06,785
-He won't use a knife, either.
-Will you use the scale?

644
00:23:06,852 --> 00:23:08,220
I won't.

645
00:23:08,286 --> 00:23:09,955
Do you have a scale in your office?

646
00:23:10,021 --> 00:23:11,990
-I don't.
-Then it's gone.

647
00:23:12,557 --> 00:23:13,692
THE SCALE GETS ABANDONED

648
00:23:13,759 --> 00:23:15,627
-Weren't you going to use it?
-I wasn't.

649
00:23:15,694 --> 00:23:18,096
They've cooked without knives before.

650
00:23:18,163 --> 00:23:21,400
<i>Despite the lack of knives,</i>
<i>they both made amazing dishes.</i>

651
00:23:21,466 --> 00:23:23,368
<i>-He cut salt with scissors.</i>
<i>-He did that.</i>

652
00:23:23,435 --> 00:23:24,469
MANY WAYS TO USE SCISSORS(?)

653
00:23:24,536 --> 00:23:26,571
-But fire is something else.
-Right.

654
00:23:26,638 --> 00:23:28,607
It's like cooking with bare hands.

655
00:23:28,673 --> 00:23:30,375
Next time, they might cover their eyes.

656
00:23:30,442 --> 00:23:32,043
-That may be the case.
-That sounds fun.

657
00:23:32,110 --> 00:23:34,880
Once again, the winner of this episode

658
00:23:34,946 --> 00:23:38,884
will receive
a bottle of the finest whiskey

659
00:23:38,950 --> 00:23:41,987
engraved with a message of hope
to celebrate the new year.

660
00:23:42,053 --> 00:23:44,890
I hope you seize the victory
and take the whiskey home.

661
00:23:45,390 --> 00:23:47,626
CHEF HYUN-SUK'S INGREDIENTS:
HAMBURGER STEAK, BROCCOLI POWDER

662
00:23:47,692 --> 00:23:49,895
TOMATO SAUCE, CARBONARA SAUCE,
FROZEN VEGETABLES, KALE, SOY MILK

663
00:23:49,961 --> 00:23:52,764
-Here's the name of the dish I'll make.
-Yes?

664
00:23:52,831 --> 00:23:54,566
Who Can Cook Without Fire?

665
00:23:54,633 --> 00:23:55,467
I-sagna.

666
00:23:55,534 --> 00:23:57,969
-I-sagna.
-I-sagna.

667
00:23:58,036 --> 00:24:00,005
-He'll make lasagna.
-I-sagna?

668
00:24:00,071 --> 00:24:02,107
-It takes a while
-Does he have the ingredients?

669
00:24:02,174 --> 00:24:05,477
to make lasagna because
the meat sauce must boil for a while,

670
00:24:05,544 --> 00:24:07,913
and because it requires
a sauce called béchamel.

671
00:24:07,979 --> 00:24:10,048
<i>-That's right.</i>
<i>-It's a white sauce</i>

672
00:24:10,115 --> 00:24:13,518
<i>made by frying butter and flour,</i>
<i>then adding bits of milk at a time.</i>

673
00:24:13,585 --> 00:24:15,687
I plan to make roux without using fire,

674
00:24:15,754 --> 00:24:18,023
-Really?
-turn it into béchamel and the meat sauce,

675
00:24:18,089 --> 00:24:19,524
and even make pasta from scratch.

676
00:24:19,791 --> 00:24:21,026
SURPRISED

677
00:24:21,092 --> 00:24:23,128
I'll make delicious lasagna for you.

678
00:24:23,195 --> 00:24:25,030
-How will he cook the pasta?
-How?

679
00:24:25,096 --> 00:24:26,465
HOW WILL HE COOK THE DOUGH?

680
00:24:26,531 --> 00:24:27,866
What will I end up eating?

681
00:24:27,933 --> 00:24:29,100
Just as I always say,

682
00:24:29,167 --> 00:24:30,335
even as we open up the new year,

683
00:24:30,402 --> 00:24:33,538
I may have to begin
another battle against myself.

684
00:24:34,206 --> 00:24:36,374
It's literally impossible…

685
00:24:36,441 --> 00:24:38,410
-A battle against aging?
-…to make lasagna

686
00:24:38,477 --> 00:24:40,545
-in just 15 minutes.
-He's aging.

687
00:24:40,612 --> 00:24:43,081
You should get a regular checkup
as soon as possible this year.

688
00:24:43,148 --> 00:24:44,749
He's fighting against age.

689
00:24:44,816 --> 00:24:46,284
You can't miss it.

690
00:24:46,351 --> 00:24:48,553
-Don't miss it.
-It'll turn into a problem.

691
00:24:49,054 --> 00:24:51,289
CHEF SUNG-JUN'S INGREDIENTS:
FROZEN VEGETABLES, SEAFOOD MIX, KALE

692
00:24:51,356 --> 00:24:53,558
SEAWEED FLAKES, KIMCHI, CRACKERS,
RED LETTUCE, THISTLE RICE, VONGOLE SAUCE

693
00:24:53,625 --> 00:24:55,994
What are you making, Chef Sung-jun?

694
00:24:56,061 --> 00:24:57,662
The dish I'm making today is

695
00:24:57,729 --> 00:24:59,831
Choi Hyun-suk's Gone, Fine Spring Day.

696
00:25:01,700 --> 00:25:04,035
CHOI HYUN-SUK'S GONE, FINE SPRING DAY

697
00:25:04,102 --> 00:25:04,936
That's rough.

698
00:25:05,003 --> 00:25:05,871
It's not fine!

699
00:25:05,937 --> 00:25:08,006
<i>When I close my eyes</i>

700
00:25:08,340 --> 00:25:09,875
I SUDDENLY REMEMBER
THE MEMORIES OF THE DAYS GONE BY

701
00:25:09,941 --> 00:25:10,976
Hyun-suk is gone?

702
00:25:11,343 --> 00:25:12,644
HOW CAN A MAN BE GONE?

703
00:25:12,711 --> 00:25:14,679
Chef Hyun-suk was born in 1972,

704
00:25:14,746 --> 00:25:16,848
which means he has now hit mid-fifties.

705
00:25:16,915 --> 00:25:18,717
-Really?
-He'll feel worse every single day.

706
00:25:18,783 --> 00:25:20,252
-He's 55 now.
-So now,

707
00:25:20,318 --> 00:25:23,221
one by one, I'll begin to steal
his signature dishes

708
00:25:23,288 --> 00:25:24,723
and turn them into mine.

709
00:25:24,789 --> 00:25:26,324
-I see.
-To begin this journey,

710
00:25:26,391 --> 00:25:30,395
I'll steal his most famous dish, vongole,

711
00:25:30,462 --> 00:25:33,031
and make vongole risotto.

712
00:25:33,098 --> 00:25:34,766
-What about the ingredients?
-How will he do that?

713
00:25:34,833 --> 00:25:36,468
I'll make vongole risotto

714
00:25:36,535 --> 00:25:38,870
and top it with something made
with Ji-tae's favorite,

715
00:25:38,937 --> 00:25:41,273
kimchi pesto.

716
00:25:41,339 --> 00:25:43,341
Making fresh pasta in the office
sounds too complicated,

717
00:25:43,408 --> 00:25:46,077
so I'll make the recipe simple enough

718
00:25:46,144 --> 00:25:47,679
so that anyone can make it.

719
00:25:47,746 --> 00:25:49,080
And he'll do it without using fire.

720
00:25:49,147 --> 00:25:50,181
Without fire or a knife.

721
00:25:50,248 --> 00:25:52,951
But you didn't have those in your fridge.

722
00:25:53,018 --> 00:25:54,653
-No.
-What will he do?

723
00:25:54,719 --> 00:25:57,722
But here's what Ji-tae wants.

724
00:25:57,789 --> 00:26:01,593
It's important to make a dish
simple enough to cook in an office,

725
00:26:01,660 --> 00:26:03,261
but what I want to do is show him

726
00:26:03,328 --> 00:26:07,098
that I can make something amazing
with the ingredients in his fridge.

727
00:26:07,165 --> 00:26:08,733
So you'll pull up the limit?

728
00:26:08,800 --> 00:26:11,303
I also have another aspect I'm focused on.

729
00:26:11,369 --> 00:26:12,637
Last year,

730
00:26:12,704 --> 00:26:14,940
I didn't pay attention
to the presentation of my dishes.

731
00:26:15,006 --> 00:26:17,175
So today, I'll pay attention to it

732
00:26:17,242 --> 00:26:20,512
and present a dish
that'll amaze you when you see it.

733
00:26:20,579 --> 00:26:22,113
-He's in high spirits.
-He is.

734
00:26:22,180 --> 00:26:24,149
That's exactly what I'm talking about.

735
00:26:24,649 --> 00:26:25,550
IT NEVER ENDS…

736
00:26:25,617 --> 00:26:27,252
How long will you keep this going?

737
00:26:27,319 --> 00:26:28,954
One speech per person is enough.

738
00:26:29,020 --> 00:26:29,854
Listen up.

739
00:26:29,921 --> 00:26:31,489
I hope they'll just start cooking.

740
00:26:31,556 --> 00:26:34,492
Can you change the order
to "Cook Without Talking"?

741
00:26:34,559 --> 00:26:37,796
-Cook Without Talking.
-She wants you to cook without talking!

742
00:26:37,862 --> 00:26:39,965
HOW ARE WE SUPPOSED TO DO THAT?

743
00:26:40,031 --> 00:26:41,333
-It'll never end.
-Not fire.

744
00:26:41,399 --> 00:26:42,634
Not a bad idea.

745
00:26:42,701 --> 00:26:45,003
It's such an honor. Thank you so much.

746
00:26:45,070 --> 00:26:47,105
-"That's enough."
-He cut them off.

747
00:26:47,172 --> 00:26:49,307
If you two wish to go on,
call each other later.

748
00:26:49,374 --> 00:26:50,909
CATCH UP LATER

749
00:26:50,976 --> 00:26:52,277
Making a call would be faster.

750
00:26:52,344 --> 00:26:53,244
-Professor Yoo.
-Yes?

751
00:26:53,311 --> 00:26:54,446
Give me your e-mail address…

752
00:26:54,512 --> 00:26:56,247
-Sorry?
-…and I'll send the rest of the things…

753
00:26:56,314 --> 00:26:58,350
-Your e-mail address?
-…I wanted to share just now…

754
00:26:58,416 --> 00:27:00,352
…in the form of a PowerPoint presentation.

755
00:27:00,418 --> 00:27:03,154
-Gosh. It's starting to get warm.
-They're fighting for grades.

756
00:27:03,221 --> 00:27:05,590
He'll grade you on your dishes,

757
00:27:05,657 --> 00:27:07,626
so let's look forward to that.

758
00:27:07,692 --> 00:27:09,661
-All right.
-One of you will have to repeat.

759
00:27:09,728 --> 00:27:12,631
Let us begin the cook-off.

760
00:27:12,697 --> 00:27:14,866
They will now compete

761
00:27:14,933 --> 00:27:19,170
and Cook Without Using Fire
as assigned by Professor Yoo.

762
00:27:19,237 --> 00:27:22,040
He's here to make
Grandpa Hyun-suk disappear.

763
00:27:22,107 --> 00:27:23,441
The freshman of the show,

764
00:27:23,508 --> 00:27:26,211
the young'un, Chef Kwon Sung-jun.

765
00:27:26,277 --> 00:27:27,912
You shall not take grandpas as a joke.

766
00:27:27,979 --> 00:27:29,481
The mature student of the show,

767
00:27:29,547 --> 00:27:32,217
Chef Choi Hyun-suk
stands against Sung-jun.

768
00:27:32,283 --> 00:27:35,086
It's a battle between the old boy
and the young boy.

769
00:27:35,153 --> 00:27:36,855
Who will rise as the winner?

770
00:27:36,921 --> 00:27:40,759
Let the 15-minute assignment begin!

771
00:27:41,526 --> 00:27:43,561
I hope you two get good grades.

772
00:27:44,129 --> 00:27:45,997
FIGHTING TO BECOME THE TOP OF THE CLASS

773
00:27:46,064 --> 00:27:48,066
I hope you two get good grades.

774
00:27:48,133 --> 00:27:49,701
All right. He's starting.

775
00:27:49,768 --> 00:27:50,935
HYUN-SUK THE STUDENT MAKES ROUX

776
00:27:51,002 --> 00:27:53,705
-He's making roux with butter and flour.
-He's making roux.

777
00:27:53,772 --> 00:27:57,242
He's cooking it in the microwave.
It should be cooked on a stove, though.

778
00:27:57,308 --> 00:27:59,310
It's a great solution.

779
00:27:59,644 --> 00:28:00,845
WHAT ABOUT SUNG-JUN?

780
00:28:01,012 --> 00:28:03,014
POURING WATER ON FROZEN VEGGIES

781
00:28:03,415 --> 00:28:06,051
AND HE ALSO USES A MICROWAVE!

782
00:28:07,185 --> 00:28:09,487
PICKING OUT KALE
FROM THE ASSORTED VEGGIE WRAPS

783
00:28:09,554 --> 00:28:12,424
Sung-jun makes holes in the kale.

784
00:28:12,490 --> 00:28:13,658
Stack them.

785
00:28:13,725 --> 00:28:15,660
That's an excellent tip. Thanks.

786
00:28:16,361 --> 00:28:17,729
He's making holes.

787
00:28:17,796 --> 00:28:18,963
-Nice.
-Right?

788
00:28:19,030 --> 00:28:20,799
I knew it. You got my back, bro.

789
00:28:20,865 --> 00:28:23,034
-He doesn't mean it.
-Only when I'm helpful.

790
00:28:23,101 --> 00:28:25,570
-Will he fry those?
-Are you using the holes?

791
00:28:25,637 --> 00:28:27,072
Are you using the holes?

792
00:28:27,138 --> 00:28:29,374
No, these are for decoration.

793
00:28:29,774 --> 00:28:33,011
HOW DOES ONE USE HOLES?

794
00:28:34,913 --> 00:28:36,915
Wait, what kind of a question was that?

795
00:28:36,981 --> 00:28:38,316
You'll get a hole in your grades!

796
00:28:39,884 --> 00:28:41,453
I thought Professor Yoo would be curious.

797
00:28:41,519 --> 00:28:44,122
-What's that? Seaweed flakes?
-Seaweed flakes.

798
00:28:44,189 --> 00:28:45,857
He's pouring olive oil into the blender.

799
00:28:45,924 --> 00:28:47,992
-That much?
-That's a lot of oil.

800
00:28:48,059 --> 00:28:50,261
-What's he doing?
-Wow.

801
00:28:50,328 --> 00:28:52,630
He's making seaweed oil.

802
00:28:53,631 --> 00:28:55,433
Chef Hyun-suk uses the hamburger steak

803
00:28:55,500 --> 00:28:57,035
He's cutting it with scissors.

804
00:28:57,102 --> 00:28:59,237
He was going to use a knife,

805
00:28:59,304 --> 00:29:01,906
but he got taunted into using scissors.

806
00:29:01,973 --> 00:29:04,442
-He snapped.
-You begin to snap more as you age.

807
00:29:04,509 --> 00:29:06,344
-It's tough to keep your temper.
-You can't help it.

808
00:29:06,411 --> 00:29:08,213
He'll suddenly snap.

809
00:29:08,279 --> 00:29:10,081
And he gets agitated
over the smallest things.

810
00:29:10,148 --> 00:29:12,016
Exactly. How unfortunate.

811
00:29:12,083 --> 00:29:15,220
He's grinding the hamburger steak
to use as meat for the lasagna sauce.

812
00:29:15,286 --> 00:29:17,021
-Right.
-For the ragu sauce.

813
00:29:17,088 --> 00:29:18,423
For his ragu sauce.

814
00:29:19,591 --> 00:29:21,326
Did the roux turn out okay?

815
00:29:21,392 --> 00:29:22,961
It's not quite ready. It's more like…

816
00:29:23,027 --> 00:29:23,928
BACK INTO THE MICROWAVE!

817
00:29:23,995 --> 00:29:25,163
It goes back in.

818
00:29:25,230 --> 00:29:26,898
It would've been ready on the stove,

819
00:29:26,965 --> 00:29:28,500
but in the microwave, it took…

820
00:29:28,566 --> 00:29:30,635
You're already
2 minutes and 30 seconds in.

821
00:29:30,969 --> 00:29:32,570
SUNG-JUN USES THE BLENDER AGAIN!

822
00:29:32,637 --> 00:29:34,572
Sung-jun uses a blender
instead of a knife.

823
00:29:34,639 --> 00:29:36,174
Kimchi.

824
00:29:37,041 --> 00:29:38,843
"Everyone, watch what I'm doing."

825
00:29:38,910 --> 00:29:41,412
-Kimchi and crackers?
-Kimchi and crackers.

826
00:29:41,479 --> 00:29:42,614
Crackers?

827
00:29:42,981 --> 00:29:45,350
SESAME OIL, OLIVE OIL

828
00:29:45,750 --> 00:29:47,786
THE PROFESSOR DOESN'T LOOK CONVINCED…

829
00:29:47,852 --> 00:29:49,888
-Those are cheese-flavored crackers.
-And red leaf lettuce.

830
00:29:49,954 --> 00:29:50,889
What? What are you doing?

831
00:29:51,623 --> 00:29:52,791
WHAT'S HE MAKING?

832
00:29:52,857 --> 00:29:54,425
And some red leaf lettuce.

833
00:29:54,492 --> 00:29:55,827
They only had to drop fire,

834
00:29:55,894 --> 00:29:57,929
but they chose to drop their knives too,

835
00:29:57,996 --> 00:29:59,964
so they're both on their blenders.

836
00:30:00,031 --> 00:30:02,433
Goodness gracious.
You can just use a knife.

837
00:30:02,500 --> 00:30:03,668
Why do you choose not to?

838
00:30:04,035 --> 00:30:05,937
THE HAMBURGER STEAK IS FULLY GROUND

839
00:30:06,004 --> 00:30:09,974
-The frozen veggie mix.
-It's frozen, so it's naturally wet.

840
00:30:10,041 --> 00:30:13,778
-Why is he using that?
-He needs veggies to make lasagna.

841
00:30:13,845 --> 00:30:16,414
-He ground everything.
-So he's using frozen veggies?

842
00:30:16,481 --> 00:30:17,882
He's moving rather fast today.

843
00:30:17,949 --> 00:30:19,050
AGAIN, INTO THE MICROWAVE!

844
00:30:19,818 --> 00:30:21,119
-Soy milk.
-It's soy milk.

845
00:30:21,186 --> 00:30:23,555
-He's mixing soy milk and roux?
-I guess so.

846
00:30:24,255 --> 00:30:25,957
What's he making there?

847
00:30:26,024 --> 00:30:27,692
He's mixing that with soy milk?

848
00:30:27,759 --> 00:30:29,194
He's salting that!

849
00:30:29,260 --> 00:30:30,628
LEFT HOOK!

850
00:30:30,695 --> 00:30:31,629
RIGHT HOOK!

851
00:30:31,696 --> 00:30:33,231
Both hands?

852
00:30:33,298 --> 00:30:34,899
Both hands?

853
00:30:35,166 --> 00:30:36,734
SALT SPRINKLING PERFORMANCE
BEFORE THE PROFESSOR

854
00:30:36,801 --> 00:30:39,003
You said you'd stop doing that this year.

855
00:30:39,070 --> 00:30:40,905
But he's slower than before.

856
00:30:42,574 --> 00:30:44,709
He's slower in 2026 than in 2025.

857
00:30:44,776 --> 00:30:46,978
-And his arms are lower.
-They don't go up as high.

858
00:30:47,045 --> 00:30:49,447
Isn't the soy milk sweetened?

859
00:30:49,514 --> 00:30:52,317
-It's not. It's unsweetened.
-It's unsweetened?

860
00:30:52,383 --> 00:30:54,285
-The color is really nice.
-Right?

861
00:30:54,352 --> 00:30:55,954
I wonder what that'll be like.

862
00:30:56,020 --> 00:30:57,889
And that goes into the microwave too.

863
00:30:57,956 --> 00:31:00,391
-Things go in and out of the microwave.
-I don't think

864
00:31:00,458 --> 00:31:03,228
the microwave has been used
this often before.

865
00:31:03,595 --> 00:31:05,530
WHAT'S SUNG-JUN GRINDING?

866
00:31:05,597 --> 00:31:06,865
That's pesto, kimchi pesto.

867
00:31:06,931 --> 00:31:08,032
Kimchi pesto?

868
00:31:08,099 --> 00:31:09,567
-Kimchi pesto?
-What did he throw in?

869
00:31:09,634 --> 00:31:13,238
-Kimchi, crackers, and lettuce.
-Lettuce?

870
00:31:13,304 --> 00:31:15,440
-It was probably a basil substitute.
-Really?

871
00:31:15,506 --> 00:31:17,075
PESTO FROM THE POWDER FRIDGE

872
00:31:17,642 --> 00:31:19,410
That's thistle rice.

873
00:31:19,477 --> 00:31:20,879
1. MIX RICE, VONGOLE SAUCE, BUTTER, WATER

874
00:31:20,945 --> 00:31:23,214
That looks like vongole risotto.

875
00:31:23,781 --> 00:31:25,917
It looks like
microwaves will be busy today.

876
00:31:25,984 --> 00:31:27,619
The microwaves are busy.

877
00:31:28,853 --> 00:31:32,690
PARBOILING FROZEN SEAFOOD MIX
WITH HOT WATER

878
00:31:32,757 --> 00:31:34,759
That's how he's cooking those?

879
00:31:34,826 --> 00:31:38,897
He's mixing seafood with the veggies.

880
00:31:38,963 --> 00:31:41,132
2. MIX SEAFOOD, VEGGIES,
VONGOLE SAUCE, OLIVE OIL, AND PEPPER

881
00:31:41,566 --> 00:31:44,502
FINDS A MOMENT TO TOSS EVERYTHING

882
00:31:44,769 --> 00:31:46,104
WHAT'S HYUN-SUK UP TO?

883
00:31:46,738 --> 00:31:47,839
MAKING LASAGNA DOUGH!

884
00:31:47,906 --> 00:31:49,641
He's making the lasagna dough… Huh?

885
00:31:49,707 --> 00:31:51,175
What's the green thing?

886
00:31:51,242 --> 00:31:53,044
-What's that powder?
-Broccoli powder.

887
00:31:53,111 --> 00:31:54,712
-Broccoli powder?
-I see.

888
00:31:54,779 --> 00:31:56,748
It looks like he added it

889
00:31:56,814 --> 00:32:00,485
to give the lasagna sheets a green color.

890
00:32:01,085 --> 00:32:02,820
HE EVEN THOUGHT OF THE COLOR!

891
00:32:02,887 --> 00:32:04,289
You have ten minutes left!

892
00:32:04,956 --> 00:32:06,291
Ten minutes left.

893
00:32:06,357 --> 00:32:07,425
-The blade won't move.
-It won't.

894
00:32:09,027 --> 00:32:09,894
ONLY IF SOMEONE COULD HELP…

895
00:32:09,961 --> 00:32:11,629
-Time is flying.
-Oh, no.

896
00:32:11,696 --> 00:32:13,398
-It won't spin.
-The blade didn't lock in.

897
00:32:13,464 --> 00:32:14,299
He should try again.

898
00:32:14,966 --> 00:32:15,867
Use your hands.

899
00:32:15,934 --> 00:32:18,236
-He's kneading the dough to make pasta?
-Yes.

900
00:32:18,303 --> 00:32:20,805
-Yes, the lasagna sheets.
-Fresh lasagna sheets.

901
00:32:20,872 --> 00:32:23,808
But does he have enough time
to do that with the microwave?

902
00:32:23,875 --> 00:32:26,878
-How will he cook the sheets?
-No idea when he'll start cooking, but…

903
00:32:26,945 --> 00:32:28,813
He can't even spot the flour.

904
00:32:28,880 --> 00:32:30,481
How will he cook that sheet?

905
00:32:30,548 --> 00:32:32,083
-Right?
-How will he cook that?

906
00:32:32,717 --> 00:32:33,985
CHECKS THE TIME

907
00:32:34,052 --> 00:32:36,654
-He doesn't have enough time.
-Hyun-suk makes fresh pasta.

908
00:32:36,721 --> 00:32:39,490
He has to make those very thin.

909
00:32:39,557 --> 00:32:41,392
-Otherwise, it won't be cooked.
-No?

910
00:32:41,459 --> 00:32:43,094
-Because he's using a microwave?
-Yes.

911
00:32:43,161 --> 00:32:45,430
-He has no time.
-He would've been done

912
00:32:45,496 --> 00:32:47,732
if he were using a knife,
but he's using scissors.

913
00:32:47,799 --> 00:32:51,736
-The professor allowed you to use a knife.
-He did.

914
00:32:51,803 --> 00:32:54,005
He gave up the knife on top of the fire.

915
00:32:54,072 --> 00:32:55,673
How will he cook that?

916
00:32:55,740 --> 00:32:57,141
In the microwave with water?

917
00:32:57,909 --> 00:32:59,444
It's the electric kettle!

918
00:33:00,645 --> 00:33:01,846
The electric kettle?

919
00:33:04,015 --> 00:33:05,350
OH MY GOODNESS

920
00:33:05,750 --> 00:33:07,618
A STROKE OF GENIUS

921
00:33:08,119 --> 00:33:09,921
NO ONE IMAGINED
HE'D USE AN ELECTRIC KETTLE

922
00:33:09,988 --> 00:33:12,190
-He's using that?
-He didn't have boiling water.

923
00:33:12,256 --> 00:33:13,324
He had no boiling water.

924
00:33:13,391 --> 00:33:15,193
That's not a bad idea.

925
00:33:15,259 --> 00:33:16,527
You're using an electric kettle?

926
00:33:16,594 --> 00:33:18,062
You must have one in the office.

927
00:33:18,129 --> 00:33:19,397
-I do.
-He does.

928
00:33:19,464 --> 00:33:22,500
-He has an electric kettle there!
-That's insane. You're a genius!

929
00:33:22,567 --> 00:33:23,901
AS IF HE FOUND A NEW GRADUATE STUDENT

930
00:33:23,968 --> 00:33:26,337
-It's like the army.
-That's how we cook <i>ramyeon</i> in the army.

931
00:33:26,404 --> 00:33:29,807
It'll keep boiling if you leave it open,
because the temperature doesn't go up.

932
00:33:29,874 --> 00:33:32,310
-Yes, he left it open.
-He did.

933
00:33:32,377 --> 00:33:35,546
-That way, the water continues to boil.
-That's amazing.

934
00:33:35,613 --> 00:33:37,248
That's so crazy. You're a genius!

935
00:33:37,315 --> 00:33:38,383
THE MATURE STUDENT'S WITS

936
00:33:38,449 --> 00:33:41,319
Everyone is impressed by Hyun-suk's idea.

937
00:33:41,386 --> 00:33:45,556
2. MIX SOY MILK SAUCE AND ROUX,
BLEND TO MAKE BÉCHAMEL

938
00:33:46,391 --> 00:33:48,092
They continue to use microwaves.

939
00:33:48,659 --> 00:33:50,194
-Seven minutes.
-They need that heat.

940
00:33:50,261 --> 00:33:53,631
The electric kettle is overflowing!

941
00:33:53,698 --> 00:33:54,899
-Is it okay?
-It's overflowing.

942
00:33:54,966 --> 00:33:56,768
-It's foaming at the mouth.
-It's overflowing.

943
00:33:56,834 --> 00:33:58,636
"Save me! Gurgle gurgle!"

944
00:33:58,703 --> 00:33:59,737
-"Gurgle!"
-"Gurgle!"

945
00:34:01,539 --> 00:34:03,641
"You can't put dough inside me!"

946
00:34:03,708 --> 00:34:05,476
"Don't use me like this!"

947
00:34:05,543 --> 00:34:07,345
It's killing the kettle.

948
00:34:07,912 --> 00:34:10,882
The kettle has never
had anything like that inside it.

949
00:34:10,948 --> 00:34:14,118
-He's the first guy to cook pasta there.
-He is. Jeez.

950
00:34:14,185 --> 00:34:15,887
It should only be used to boil water.

951
00:34:15,953 --> 00:34:17,221
ANGER DYING DOWN

952
00:34:17,555 --> 00:34:19,390
CAME TO AN AMICABLE AGREEMENT

953
00:34:19,457 --> 00:34:21,692
You have 6 minutes and 30 seconds.

954
00:34:21,759 --> 00:34:24,595
-Thistle rice comes out of the microwave.
-I see.

955
00:34:24,662 --> 00:34:25,797
-He's adding water.
-Water?

956
00:34:25,863 --> 00:34:26,864
-What's that?
-Is that oil?

957
00:34:26,931 --> 00:34:28,466
-It's water.
-Water?

958
00:34:28,533 --> 00:34:29,801
I'm figuring out the texture.

959
00:34:29,867 --> 00:34:32,303
You're adding water?
It sounds like you're making porridge.

960
00:34:32,370 --> 00:34:34,605
You can eat porridge like that
after a shabu-shabu meal.

961
00:34:34,672 --> 00:34:36,374
You're right. That's what it is.

962
00:34:36,441 --> 00:34:39,710
-It's the shabu-shabu porridge.
-They serve you porridge as you finish up.

963
00:34:41,145 --> 00:34:42,413
Everything got blended.

964
00:34:42,480 --> 00:34:44,048
It's seaweed oil.

965
00:34:44,348 --> 00:34:45,183
OH

966
00:34:45,583 --> 00:34:47,618
He's adding just the seaweed aroma.

967
00:34:47,685 --> 00:34:49,120
-For the risotto?
-Yes.

968
00:34:49,187 --> 00:34:50,621
That'll add some umami.

969
00:34:50,688 --> 00:34:53,591
Wow. That's fascinating.
How do they do this?

970
