1462
00:53:22,465 --> 00:53:23,633
MOVING QUICKLY!

1463
00:53:24,067 --> 00:53:25,902
PREPPED VEGGIES AND SEAFOOD IN 2 MINUTES!

1464
00:53:25,969 --> 00:53:28,205
That's fascinating. How does she do that?

1465
00:53:28,271 --> 00:53:29,506
SOY MILK

1466
00:53:29,573 --> 00:53:31,208
You're using that much soy milk?

1467
00:53:31,274 --> 00:53:32,242
3 SOY MILK PACKS

1468
00:53:32,309 --> 00:53:34,110
How many packs are you…

1469
00:53:34,177 --> 00:53:35,212
He's making soy milk soup.

1470
00:53:35,278 --> 00:53:37,147
He's using lots of soy milk too.

1471
00:53:37,214 --> 00:53:38,181
-Sugar?
-You'll see later.

1472
00:53:38,248 --> 00:53:39,482
-All right.
-Salt? Huh?

1473
00:53:40,584 --> 00:53:41,618
AND EGGS!

1474
00:53:41,685 --> 00:53:43,353
-Eggs.
-Egg yolks.

1475
00:53:43,420 --> 00:53:45,422
The yolks for the sabayon base.

1476
00:53:45,488 --> 00:53:46,556
He uses just the yolks.

1477
00:53:46,623 --> 00:53:49,292
He'll whip it with some sugar.

1478
00:53:49,359 --> 00:53:50,293
THE FIFTH EGG GOES ON A TRAY

1479
00:53:51,161 --> 00:53:52,963
The chicken breast pieces…

1480
00:53:53,029 --> 00:53:54,497
Aren't those ready-to-eat?

1481
00:53:54,564 --> 00:53:56,299
-They're all raw.
-They are?

1482
00:53:56,366 --> 00:53:57,534
Some of them are raw.

1483
00:53:57,601 --> 00:53:58,602
2. GRIND CHICKEN AND DUMPLINGS

1484
00:53:58,735 --> 00:53:59,936
NEXT, CRACKERS!

1485
00:54:00,003 --> 00:54:02,138
-He's using crackers.
-You're grinding crackers too?

1486
00:54:02,205 --> 00:54:05,208
-Nam-no grinds some crackers too.
-Crackers?

1487
00:54:05,275 --> 00:54:07,677
-Crackers for a healthy dish?
-I wonder.

1488
00:54:08,511 --> 00:54:09,746
-Crackers.
-However,

1489
00:54:09,813 --> 00:54:10,914
those are baked.

1490
00:54:10,981 --> 00:54:13,850
-And not deep-fried.
-They were baked.

1491
00:54:13,917 --> 00:54:16,686
-Can I really eat lots of that?
-Sure.

1492
00:54:16,753 --> 00:54:18,989
Maybe we should check on him.

1493
00:54:19,055 --> 00:54:21,758
-That's butter.
-My gosh. Look at the butter.

1494
00:54:21,825 --> 00:54:23,193
-What happened?
-Look at that.

1495
00:54:24,561 --> 00:54:27,063
That's healthier
than what Nam-no usually eats.

1496
00:54:27,130 --> 00:54:30,400
If it's healthier than what he eats,
then it's healthy.

1497
00:54:31,468 --> 00:54:32,369
He doesn't use those.

1498
00:54:32,435 --> 00:54:34,471
You aren't graded on a curve.

1499
00:54:34,537 --> 00:54:35,872
That'll keep him alive forever.

1500
00:54:36,773 --> 00:54:39,309
-Forever.
-He'll be graded on points.

1501
00:54:40,277 --> 00:54:41,211
Is that fresh pollack?

1502
00:54:41,278 --> 00:54:42,579
-Frozen.
-Frozen pollack.

1503
00:54:42,646 --> 00:54:44,648
The pollack from
the <i>dongtae-tang </i>meal kit<i>?</i>

1504
00:54:44,714 --> 00:54:46,449
Right. <i>Dongtae-tang.</i>

1505
00:54:47,083 --> 00:54:49,619
-You're only using the fish meat.
-I am.

1506
00:54:49,686 --> 00:54:51,288
She's removing the bones.

1507
00:54:51,921 --> 00:54:52,922
FILLETING UNDER THE SKIN

1508
00:54:52,989 --> 00:54:55,258
-Watch your hand.
-She's removing the skin

1509
00:54:55,325 --> 00:54:58,194
-to get rid of the excessive fishy smell.
-I see.

1510
00:54:58,261 --> 00:55:01,731
-In case it gets too fishy.
-Yes, she's making seafood balls.

1511
00:55:01,798 --> 00:55:04,801
You're right. It'd be awful
to eat a fishy seafood ball.

1512
00:55:05,368 --> 00:55:09,406
2. MAKE SEAFOOD BALL BATTER
WITH POLLACK FILLET AND BROCCOLI POWDER

1513
00:55:09,472 --> 00:55:11,675
Chef Eun-yeong prepares seafood balls.

1514
00:55:11,741 --> 00:55:12,909
SPEEDY HANDS

1515
00:55:13,710 --> 00:55:14,744
Wow.

1516
00:55:15,312 --> 00:55:17,914
-She's fast, isn't she?
-She's incredible. Truly.

1517
00:55:17,981 --> 00:55:19,382
-She moves very fast.
-She does.

1518
00:55:19,449 --> 00:55:22,252
She finished second
in the last championship.

1519
00:55:22,319 --> 00:55:24,287
-They're both making balls.
-Yes, one's seafood

1520
00:55:24,354 --> 00:55:26,156
and the other is chicken.

1521
00:55:26,222 --> 00:55:28,291
-She's deep-frying!
-She makes seafood balls.

1522
00:55:28,358 --> 00:55:30,193
-Deep-frying?
-I'll fry these lightly, then boil.

1523
00:55:30,260 --> 00:55:31,227
She's fast.

1524
00:55:31,294 --> 00:55:32,729
-Wow.
-She really is.

1525
00:55:32,796 --> 00:55:34,331
It looks so good.

1526
00:55:34,397 --> 00:55:37,367
-He already says the fish ball looks good.
-The fried balls look good.

1527
00:55:37,434 --> 00:55:38,802
-It looks good.
-It looks good.

1528
00:55:39,002 --> 00:55:39,903
READING THE ROOM

1529
00:55:39,969 --> 00:55:40,870
It looks good.

1530
00:55:41,137 --> 00:55:42,405
HEHE

1531
00:55:42,472 --> 00:55:43,473
-Mine looks good.
-It looks good.

1532
00:55:43,540 --> 00:55:46,543
-You have 11 minutes left.
-What?

1533
00:55:46,609 --> 00:55:48,178
He's using meat too.

1534
00:55:48,244 --> 00:55:51,014
He made a hole
in the middle of the hamburger steak.

1535
00:55:51,081 --> 00:55:53,049
The boiling carrot juice reminds me

1536
00:55:53,116 --> 00:55:54,984
-of spicy seafood soup.
-You're right.

1537
00:55:55,051 --> 00:55:58,288
-Spicy seafood soup. It's overflowing.
-It's overflowing.

1538
00:55:58,355 --> 00:56:00,290
-It'll burn.
-It'll taste nice with some pollacks.

1539
00:56:00,357 --> 00:56:01,925
That sounds perfect.

1540
00:56:01,991 --> 00:56:03,693
Do you need some? I got some.

1541
00:56:03,760 --> 00:56:05,595
I want to throw in some <i>sujebi </i>too.

1542
00:56:05,662 --> 00:56:08,898
All Korean men
are infatuated with red soup.

1543
00:56:11,368 --> 00:56:15,205
5. MIX SOY SAUCE, COOKING WINE, SUGAR

1544
00:56:15,271 --> 00:56:16,806
MIX WITH CHICKEN BREAST BATTER

1545
00:56:17,574 --> 00:56:18,842
MIXING

1546
00:56:19,509 --> 00:56:20,543
TASTING

1547
00:56:20,610 --> 00:56:22,278
Just now, Chef Nam-no

1548
00:56:22,345 --> 00:56:25,181
chewed on raw chicken meat
to taste how it's seasoned.

1549
00:56:25,248 --> 00:56:26,349
Most people would spit it out…

1550
00:56:26,416 --> 00:56:28,451
-He ate it?
-He swallowed it?

1551
00:56:28,518 --> 00:56:30,086
-Is that okay?
-But salmonella poisoning…

1552
00:56:30,153 --> 00:56:31,588
It was a tiny bit, but still.

1553
00:56:31,654 --> 00:56:33,323
6. FILL THE PATTY HOLE WITH CHICKEN BATTER

1554
00:56:33,390 --> 00:56:35,125
He's good with salmonella.

1555
00:56:35,191 --> 00:56:36,559
That's his biggest weakness.

1556
00:56:36,626 --> 00:56:38,561
He never spits out what he eats.

1557
00:56:38,628 --> 00:56:40,530
I can beat salmonella poisoning.

1558
00:56:40,597 --> 00:56:43,933
There's no way
Chef Nam-no's dish tastes bad.

1559
00:56:44,000 --> 00:56:46,369
-He only used delicious ingredients.
-Yes.

1560
00:56:47,437 --> 00:56:48,738
FLOUR

1561
00:56:50,173 --> 00:56:51,674
-Flour, egg, breadcrumbs?
-Flour, egg, breadcrumbs?

1562
00:56:51,741 --> 00:56:54,110
-Wait, are you deep-frying?
-The ground crackers?

1563
00:56:54,177 --> 00:56:56,980
-He's using it like breadcrumbs?
-He is.

1564
00:56:57,046 --> 00:56:58,915
Wait, is this a healthy dish?

1565
00:56:58,982 --> 00:57:01,951
-Hold on…
-Wait, how is this healthy?

1566
00:57:02,018 --> 00:57:03,953
-Wait.
-No, it's so healthy,

1567
00:57:04,020 --> 00:57:05,722
and the portion is huge.

1568
00:57:05,789 --> 00:57:08,391
-"The portion is huge"?
-"The portion is huge"?

1569
00:57:09,058 --> 00:57:11,060
I think you're on a different page.

1570
00:57:11,127 --> 00:57:12,929
How are healthiness and portion related?

1571
00:57:12,996 --> 00:57:15,565
Yes, how are healthiness
and portion related?

1572
00:57:15,632 --> 00:57:16,833
When he heard "healthy dish,"

1573
00:57:16,900 --> 00:57:20,837
he thought he had to let him eat
lots of calories to help him grow.

1574
00:57:20,904 --> 00:57:24,107
It's like when people say,
"Hey, you look healthier."

1575
00:57:24,174 --> 00:57:27,343
-"You look good."
-I think the student has misunderstood.

1576
00:57:27,410 --> 00:57:28,445
Our elders would go,

1577
00:57:28,511 --> 00:57:32,682
-"You're too thin! Put on some weight!"
-Yes, that's unhealthy.

1578
00:57:32,749 --> 00:57:34,684
-Eating well equals healthy.
-Chubby means healthy.

1579
00:57:34,751 --> 00:57:37,720
The word "healthy" may have had
a different ring for the two of them.

1580
00:57:37,787 --> 00:57:39,989
Nam-no often gets told
that he looks healthy.

1581
00:57:40,056 --> 00:57:42,892
-And the same goes for Ho-young.
-I do.

1582
00:57:42,959 --> 00:57:46,029
Something you can have
and share with all your friends too.

1583
00:57:46,095 --> 00:57:49,632
He must've thought he had to make a lot
to make a healthy dish.

1584
00:57:49,899 --> 00:57:52,135
HOW DID SECOND FROM THE TOP
COMPREHEND THE ASSIGNMENT?

1585
00:57:52,202 --> 00:57:53,603
-Tofu noodles.
-Tofu noodles?

1586
00:57:53,670 --> 00:57:54,971
-Tofu noodles.
-That's healthy.

1587
00:57:55,038 --> 00:57:57,307
-That's healthy.
-That's good.

1588
00:57:57,373 --> 00:58:00,410
It's made with soy protein,
so it's healthy.

1589
00:58:00,643 --> 00:58:01,911
GARLIC

1590
00:58:03,146 --> 00:58:04,781
What's she doing? Making the sauce?

1591
00:58:04,848 --> 00:58:05,915
It's the sauce.

1592
00:58:05,982 --> 00:58:08,084
5. BOIL WATER, CRUSHED GARLIC,
AND SOY SAUCE

1593
00:58:08,151 --> 00:58:09,819
Six minutes and fifty seconds.

1594
00:58:09,886 --> 00:58:11,287
About seven minutes left.

1595
00:58:12,489 --> 00:58:13,957
6. PARBOIL VEGGIES AND BOIL IN SOUP

1596
00:58:14,023 --> 00:58:16,292
Chef Eun-yeong looks quite focused.

1597
00:58:16,359 --> 00:58:18,962
-The seafood balls are ready.
-The seafood balls.

1598
00:58:21,364 --> 00:58:23,967
Those seafood balls look awesome.

1599
00:58:24,801 --> 00:58:29,639
I wonder if it'll be cooked all the way.
The chicken on the inside won't cook.

1600
00:58:29,706 --> 00:58:31,541
Why don't you microwave those
before grilling?

1601
00:58:33,243 --> 00:58:34,310
He won't even listen.

1602
00:58:34,377 --> 00:58:36,779
-He won't even listen.
-He won't answer the question.

1603
00:58:36,846 --> 00:58:38,414
Why are you pulling them out?

1604
00:58:38,481 --> 00:58:40,149
He's going to microwave those.

1605
00:58:40,216 --> 00:58:41,551
Wait, it's a metal pan.

1606
00:58:41,618 --> 00:58:43,286
-You can't use metal.
-It's the oven.

1607
00:58:43,353 --> 00:58:44,754
-Not the microwave.
-The oven, right?

1608
00:58:44,821 --> 00:58:47,190
-Is it?
-Yes, it's the oven! I'm a chef!

1609
00:58:47,257 --> 00:58:49,425
-Did you press start?
-Press start.

1610
00:58:49,492 --> 00:58:50,693
I did.

1611
00:58:50,760 --> 00:58:52,495
-You did? No.
-You didn't.

1612
00:58:52,562 --> 00:58:53,963
You didn't.

1613
00:58:54,030 --> 00:58:55,632
-I didn't?
-No, you didn't.

1614
00:58:55,698 --> 00:58:57,667
-You didn't.
-And the top…

1615
00:58:57,734 --> 00:58:59,502
You must remove the top pan.

1616
00:58:59,569 --> 00:59:01,938
-It won't work with the top pan?
-It sounds like he's in trouble.

1617
00:59:02,005 --> 00:59:04,274
-Pull out the top pan.
-You're in trouble.

1618
00:59:04,340 --> 00:59:05,608
-Yes, pull it out.
-Pull it out.

1619
00:59:05,675 --> 00:59:07,477
-Press start again.
-Yes, press start.

1620
00:59:08,945 --> 00:59:10,547
HE'S MORE DISTRACTED WHEN FOCUSED

1621
00:59:10,613 --> 00:59:12,482
-Calm down.
-How many times do you have to travel?

1622
00:59:12,549 --> 00:59:14,117
He's making the sabayon.

1623
00:59:14,183 --> 00:59:17,654
-The definition of healthiness may vary.
-Sabayon. His definition is the portion.

1624
00:59:17,720 --> 00:59:19,589
-The whisk is too small.
-Yes.

1625
00:59:19,656 --> 00:59:20,757
Why is it so tiny?

1626
00:59:22,892 --> 00:59:23,826
Why is the whisk so tiny?

1627
00:59:23,893 --> 00:59:24,727
TRADE

1628
00:59:25,461 --> 00:59:26,596
HEHE

1629
00:59:26,796 --> 00:59:27,764
DOUBLE-BOILING OVER HOT WATER

1630
00:59:27,897 --> 00:59:29,332
OFF THE HEAT

1631
00:59:29,766 --> 00:59:32,368
AND RETURNING TO DOUBLE-BOILING

1632
00:59:33,269 --> 00:59:34,537
MUST WHIP RAPIDLY FOR A WHILE
TO MAKE SABAYON

1633
00:59:34,604 --> 00:59:36,773
Nam-no is fighting against himself.

1634
00:59:36,839 --> 00:59:38,808
He's reaching that texture.

1635
00:59:38,875 --> 00:59:40,443
-Whoa.
-Wow.

1636
00:59:41,711 --> 00:59:43,513
He's adding butter now.

1637
00:59:44,280 --> 00:59:46,049
-Gosh. How healthy.
-Butter.

1638
00:59:46,115 --> 00:59:48,918
Wow, those calories
are the healthiest ever.

1639
00:59:48,985 --> 00:59:50,320
High fat, low carbs.

1640
00:59:51,154 --> 00:59:53,022
-High fat, low carbs.
-High fat, low carbs?

1641
00:59:53,656 --> 00:59:55,825
I'm telling you,
butter really is good for you!

1642
00:59:55,892 --> 00:59:58,494
-He has crackers, but it's low-carb.
-He used crackers.

1643
00:59:58,561 --> 01:00:00,930
We'll make you healthy, Professor Yoo.

1644
01:00:01,197 --> 01:00:02,498
CAN YOU STOP ME?

1645
01:00:02,565 --> 01:00:05,335
You can enjoy it
with all of your students!

1646
01:00:06,235 --> 01:00:08,137
We'll make you chubbier.

1647
01:00:09,138 --> 01:00:10,773
I'll use this method for <i>Vigilante 2.</i>

1648
01:00:11,341 --> 01:00:14,877
8. POUR BUTTER INTO SABAYON WHILE WHISKING

1649
01:00:14,944 --> 01:00:16,312
Five minutes!

1650
01:00:16,379 --> 01:00:17,714
-Jung-hwan?
-I'll go.

1651
01:00:17,780 --> 01:00:19,048
-A healthy dish.
-A healthy dish.

1652
01:00:19,115 --> 01:00:21,551
-Who'll make it taste healthy?
-Mine is so healthy.

1653
01:00:21,618 --> 01:00:24,721
Did Chef Nam-no understand the assignment?

1654
01:00:24,787 --> 01:00:26,889
That does look so good, though.

1655
01:00:26,956 --> 01:00:29,425
-Half egg, half butter.
-Yes.

1656
01:00:29,492 --> 01:00:31,160
-The seafood balls are ready.
-Yes, try some.

1657
01:00:31,227 --> 01:00:32,295
Will you refry these?

1658
01:00:32,362 --> 01:00:33,429
No, you can try it.

1659
01:00:33,496 --> 01:00:34,497
Should I try the seafood ball?

1660
01:00:34,564 --> 01:00:36,966
-Try a seafood ball.
-That looks so good.

1661
01:00:37,033 --> 01:00:37,934
<i>Seafood ball</i>

1662
01:00:38,001 --> 01:00:41,004
So? Attack Yoon Nam-no.

1663
01:00:41,070 --> 01:00:43,139
Is it enough to take him down?

1664
01:00:43,206 --> 01:00:45,274
That looks so good.

1665
01:00:45,642 --> 01:00:46,876
FROWN

1666
01:00:46,943 --> 01:00:47,944
-What is it?
-It must be good.

1667
01:00:48,011 --> 01:00:49,178
-Hey.
-Calm down.

1668
01:00:49,245 --> 01:00:50,780
You should've told me it's hot.

1669
01:00:51,347 --> 01:00:52,448
It must be quite hot.

1670
01:00:52,515 --> 01:00:54,851
Of course. She just deep-fried those.

1671
01:00:55,418 --> 01:00:56,686
Yoon Nam-no

1672
01:00:56,753 --> 01:00:57,787
is floating away

1673
01:00:57,854 --> 01:00:59,555
along with frozen pollack.

1674
01:00:59,622 --> 01:01:01,457
-It's good.
-It's good?

1675
01:01:02,659 --> 01:01:03,993
He's using tofu noodles too.

1676
01:01:04,060 --> 01:01:05,595
Stir-fried tofu?

1677
01:01:05,662 --> 01:01:07,997
It's the teriyaki sauce he made earlier.

1678
01:01:08,064 --> 01:01:09,098
What's that?

1679
01:01:09,165 --> 01:01:10,199
Lemon juice.

1680
01:01:10,266 --> 01:01:11,768
He's adding that much lemon juice?

1681
01:01:11,834 --> 01:01:13,670
It's usually an ingredient for sabayon.

1682
01:01:13,736 --> 01:01:15,705
-That's a lot.
-Is it okay?

1683
01:01:15,772 --> 01:01:16,739
Is it good?

1684
01:01:16,806 --> 01:01:17,640
NODS

1685
01:01:17,707 --> 01:01:18,541
It's good.

1686
01:01:18,608 --> 01:01:21,544
He's so good. How are they all so good?

1687
01:01:21,611 --> 01:01:24,180
Hey, Nam-no. Check out that texture.

1688
01:01:24,247 --> 01:01:25,481
He's been doing that for five minutes.

1689
01:01:25,548 --> 01:01:27,016
-It's for the sabayon.
-He's been on it for a while.

1690
01:01:27,083 --> 01:01:29,752
-Taste the sabayon.
-Is the sabayon finished?

1691
01:01:29,819 --> 01:01:30,787
A BIG SCOOP OF SAUCE

1692
01:01:30,853 --> 01:01:32,321
Three minutes.

1693
01:01:33,156 --> 01:01:34,657
Why do you taste it so many times?

1694
01:01:34,724 --> 01:01:36,659
-Why do you keep eating it?
-He ate it again?

1695
01:01:36,726 --> 01:01:38,161
You already tasted it before.

1696
01:01:38,227 --> 01:01:40,663
He put lots of work into the sabayon.

1697
01:01:41,230 --> 01:01:43,766
He's not tasting it,
he's just eating the noodles.

1698
01:01:43,833 --> 01:01:46,202
-He ate so much.
-That was almost half of it.

1699
01:01:46,269 --> 01:01:47,904
-Sabayon.
-Sabayon.

1700
01:01:47,970 --> 01:01:49,305
So?

1701
01:01:49,372 --> 01:01:51,708
Is it worth an A plus?

1702
01:01:55,645 --> 01:01:57,346
-A plus?
-So far, it's just an A.

1703
01:01:57,413 --> 01:01:59,816
-It's an A so far.
-It's not done yet.

1704
01:01:59,882 --> 01:02:01,017
You've come a long way.

1705
01:02:01,084 --> 01:02:03,386
-What's that?
-Salt? What is that?

1706
01:02:03,453 --> 01:02:04,620
-Soy milk.
-Soy milk.

1707
01:02:04,687 --> 01:02:07,557
I think he added
protein powder to soy milk.

1708
01:02:07,623 --> 01:02:08,691
The boiled soy milk?

1709
01:02:08,758 --> 01:02:10,359
He's blending it.

1710
01:02:10,426 --> 01:02:12,462
-Two minutes left.
-Why is he blending it?

1711
01:02:12,528 --> 01:02:14,230
-What's that for?
-Two minutes!

1712
01:02:14,297 --> 01:02:16,666
I get it. Is he making foam?

1713
01:02:16,733 --> 01:02:18,601
-By using that?
-He made foam.

1714
01:02:18,668 --> 01:02:20,770
LIKE A CAPPUCCINO

1715
01:02:20,970 --> 01:02:22,004
BOILING OIL

1716
01:02:22,071 --> 01:02:23,239
She's making green onion oil.

1717
01:02:24,207 --> 01:02:25,641
LASTLY, FINISHING THE SOUP!

1718
01:02:25,708 --> 01:02:29,145
Her soup reminds me
of scorched rice soup with seafood.

1719
01:02:29,212 --> 01:02:30,747
What's this called?

1720
01:02:30,813 --> 01:02:32,715
-It's like seafood noodles in thick broth.
-Seafood noodles.

1721
01:02:32,782 --> 01:02:33,883
She must've added starch.

1722
01:02:33,950 --> 01:02:36,853
-I love those noodles.
-That one looks so good.

1723
01:02:36,919 --> 01:02:39,388
I think Chef Eun-yeong is moving faster.

1724
01:02:39,455 --> 01:02:42,425
-She's almost done.
-It does seem healthy.

1725
01:02:43,259 --> 01:02:44,427
DUMPLING HAMBURGER STEAK IN THE OVEN

1726
01:02:44,494 --> 01:02:47,063
Do you think it's fully cooked?

1727
01:02:47,130 --> 01:02:48,931
-Cut it open.
-I hope these came out well.

1728
01:02:48,998 --> 01:02:50,299
-Is it cooked?
-Temperature check.

1729
01:02:50,633 --> 01:02:52,068
HEHEHE

1730
01:02:52,135 --> 01:02:55,371
-It's going back in!
-Hey, try the microwave!

1731
01:02:55,438 --> 01:02:57,340
-Microwave is faster!
-You got no time!

1732
01:02:57,406 --> 01:03:00,476
-It's metal!
-Then you can't put that in there.

1733
01:03:00,543 --> 01:03:02,345
I don't think it's fully cooked yet.

1734
01:03:03,579 --> 01:03:05,114
CARROT SABAYON

1735
01:03:05,181 --> 01:03:06,949
Forty-five seconds!

1736
01:03:07,016 --> 01:03:08,751
-Forty-five seconds!
-Yes.

1737
01:03:09,952 --> 01:03:12,321
12. TOP SABAYON WITH TOFU NOODLES

1738
01:03:12,388 --> 01:03:13,790
Eun-yeong begins to plate her food.

1739
01:03:13,856 --> 01:03:15,792
Chef Eun-yeong is almost done.

1740
01:03:15,858 --> 01:03:17,293
She's on fire.

1741
01:03:17,360 --> 01:03:19,328
1ST FLOOR, TOFU NOODLES
2ND FLOOR, SEAFOOD BALLS

1742
01:03:19,762 --> 01:03:20,797
It looks healthy.

1743
01:03:20,863 --> 01:03:23,099
It looks like a Chinese dish,

1744
01:03:23,166 --> 01:03:25,201
and it looks healthy, Eun-yeong.

1745
01:03:25,268 --> 01:03:27,303
FINISHING WITH GREEN ONION!

1746
01:03:28,137 --> 01:03:30,039
What about that one?

1747
01:03:30,106 --> 01:03:31,440
What now?

1748
01:03:31,507 --> 01:03:33,709
Just cut it in half
and grill it in the pan!

1749
01:03:33,776 --> 01:03:35,678
-Cut it in half and grill it!
-It's good.

1750
01:03:35,745 --> 01:03:38,047
You have 25 seconds left.

1751
01:03:38,114 --> 01:03:39,649
ON TOP OF THE STIR-FRIED TOFU NOODLES

1752
01:03:40,950 --> 01:03:42,885
Eun-yeong is done!

1753
01:03:42,952 --> 01:03:45,588
-That one looks good.
-Fifteen seconds, Nam-no!

1754
01:03:45,655 --> 01:03:47,290
-Fifteen seconds, Nam-no!
-The foam.

1755
01:03:47,356 --> 01:03:49,525
-The foam.
-Ten. Nine.

1756
01:03:49,592 --> 01:03:51,194
-Gosh.
-Eight.

1757
01:03:51,260 --> 01:03:54,297
-Seven. Six. Five.
-Seven. Six. Five.

1758
01:03:54,363 --> 01:03:56,732
-Four. Three.
-Four. Three.

1759
01:03:56,799 --> 01:03:58,234
-Two. One.
-Two. One.

1760
01:03:58,301 --> 01:03:59,702
-Time's up.
-Time's up.

1761
01:03:59,769 --> 01:04:01,671
Nam-no is done.

1762
01:04:01,737 --> 01:04:04,073
-I hope the insides are cooked.
-Wow.

1763
01:04:04,140 --> 01:04:06,475
It looks rather nice.

1764
01:04:06,542 --> 01:04:10,346
He added some foam
to make it look like a healthier dish.

1765
01:04:10,413 --> 01:04:11,848
THE FINAL TOUCH OF FOAM DID IT

1766
01:04:12,215 --> 01:04:13,049
2ND PERIOD IS DONE TOO!

1767
01:04:13,115 --> 01:04:15,518
He whipped the soy milk
and made it into foam.

1768
01:04:15,585 --> 01:04:18,154
It's like watching a circus show.

1769
01:04:18,221 --> 01:04:19,589
Wow.

1770
01:04:19,655 --> 01:04:24,327
And now, Professor Yoo's assignment
has been finished once again.

1771
01:04:24,393 --> 01:04:26,562
There was a discrepancy

1772
01:04:26,629 --> 01:04:29,298
in the definition of healthiness
among the students.

1773
01:04:29,365 --> 01:04:31,234
Perhaps they needed more explanation.

1774
01:04:31,300 --> 01:04:32,735
Their comprehension skills…

1775
01:04:32,802 --> 01:04:34,670
At times, I have to bulk up,

1776
01:04:34,737 --> 01:04:37,173
so he must've thought of that
and made me that dish.

1777
01:04:37,240 --> 01:04:39,709
-A healthy way to bulk up.
-Healthiness.

1778
01:04:39,775 --> 01:04:42,745
Some people want
their insides to be healthy,

1779
01:04:42,812 --> 01:04:46,415
but some others want to appear healthy.

1780
01:04:46,482 --> 01:04:49,886
Please try
Chef Eun-yeong's healthy dish first.

1781
01:04:49,952 --> 01:04:54,657
A HEALTHY SEAFOOD BALL SOUP
FILLED WITH TOFU NOODLES

1782
01:04:55,691 --> 01:04:59,362
CHEF PARK EUN-YEONG'S ATTACK YOON NAM-NO

1783
01:04:59,428 --> 01:05:01,931
It reminds me of royal court cuisine.

1784
01:05:01,998 --> 01:05:05,301
-Anyone can see how healthy it is.
-It looks so healthy.

1785
01:05:05,768 --> 01:05:06,602
WOW…

1786
01:05:06,669 --> 01:05:08,838
-The professor looks surprised.
-It looks so healthy.

1787
01:05:08,905 --> 01:05:11,407
-It looks so good.
-It smells great.

1788
01:05:11,474 --> 01:05:13,342
It's a shame that I have to eat this.

1789
01:05:13,409 --> 01:05:16,479
-It looks so fantastic.
-Yes.

1790
01:05:16,545 --> 01:05:18,514
Thank you for the dish.

1791
01:05:19,582 --> 01:05:20,950
Will it taste healthy?

1792
01:05:21,651 --> 01:05:23,853
That's Attack Yoon Nam-no.

1793
01:05:24,887 --> 01:05:26,122
MMM

1794
01:05:26,923 --> 01:05:28,257
Wow.

1795
01:05:28,858 --> 01:05:30,259
This is so good.

1796
01:05:31,160 --> 01:05:32,361
RELIEVED, ANXIOUS

1797
01:05:32,428 --> 01:05:36,599
Is the soup thick or something like that?

1798
01:05:36,666 --> 01:05:38,434
-Is it soy-based?
-And salt and pepper.

1799
01:05:38,501 --> 01:05:39,969
SLURPING THE VEGGIES AND SOUP

1800
01:05:40,036 --> 01:05:44,006
The seafood balls give out
some broth as the soup boils.

1801
01:05:44,073 --> 01:05:46,475
-And it has veggies.
-It's so…

1802
01:05:46,542 --> 01:05:50,379
First of all, the soup tastes so clean.

1803
01:05:50,446 --> 01:05:51,614
It looks good.

1804
01:05:51,681 --> 01:05:52,848
-It really is.
-Tofu noodles.

1805
01:05:52,915 --> 01:05:56,352
When those tofu noodles meet warm soup,

1806
01:05:56,419 --> 01:05:58,154
it shines through.

1807
01:05:58,721 --> 01:06:01,657
-It becomes very soft.
-It's usually kind of tough.

1808
01:06:01,724 --> 01:06:04,727
He eats tofu noodles
like they were actual noodles.

1809
01:06:04,794 --> 01:06:07,096
VACUUMING THE TOFU NOODLES

1810
01:06:07,163 --> 01:06:09,699
-It must be good.
-It looks so healthy.

1811
01:06:11,367 --> 01:06:12,568
-A plus?
-Wow.

1812
01:06:12,635 --> 01:06:15,171
PRACTICAL ASSIGNMENT
TASTE: A PLUS

1813
01:06:15,237 --> 01:06:16,706
My gosh.

1814
01:06:16,772 --> 01:06:18,074
It must be an A plus.

1815
01:06:18,140 --> 01:06:22,211
The professor is amazed.
"This student is good."

1816
01:06:22,778 --> 01:06:24,447
Was she this good?

1817
01:06:24,513 --> 01:06:27,783
How did she make this
with those ingredients?

1818
01:06:28,784 --> 01:06:31,721
SLURPING

1819
01:06:31,787 --> 01:06:35,358
As he mentioned before,
it must feel like a big treat.

1820
01:06:35,424 --> 01:06:37,360
She made such a healthy dish for him.

1821
01:06:38,894 --> 01:06:40,896
What's the soup like?

1822
01:06:41,697 --> 01:06:43,032
The soup

1823
01:06:43,099 --> 01:06:44,467
is immaculate.

1824
01:06:44,533 --> 01:06:45,601
Immaculate.

1825
01:06:45,668 --> 01:06:47,636
HAPPY, SAD

1826
01:06:47,870 --> 01:06:49,505
ENVIOUS

1827
01:06:49,572 --> 01:06:51,574
-Nice try.
-The way

1828
01:06:51,640 --> 01:06:54,143
the seafood balls were fried

1829
01:06:54,210 --> 01:06:58,280
mix cleanly and nicely
with the soup in perfect harmony.

1830
01:06:58,347 --> 01:07:01,217
The balance of the dish is perfect.

1831
01:07:01,283 --> 01:07:02,918
-Is it seasoned nicely?
-Yes.

1832
01:07:02,985 --> 01:07:04,954
Look at him digging in.

1833
01:07:05,021 --> 01:07:08,290
On a cold day,
he can walk back into his office

1834
01:07:08,357 --> 01:07:09,792
and eat that to warm up.

1835
01:07:10,659 --> 01:07:12,828
It feels comforting.

1836
01:07:12,895 --> 01:07:15,064
-How heartwarming.
-The food she made

1837
01:07:15,131 --> 01:07:16,732
just made him feel comforted.

1838
01:07:16,799 --> 01:07:17,867
ANXIOUS

1839
01:07:17,933 --> 01:07:19,602
I'm about to shed a tear.

1840
01:07:19,668 --> 01:07:22,405
He feels like crying,
as if he's comforted.

1841
01:07:22,471 --> 01:07:24,473
I want to try making this.

1842
01:07:25,341 --> 01:07:27,676
-You watched her and wanted to make this?
-Yes.

1843
01:07:27,743 --> 01:07:29,011
With the seafood ball.

1844
01:07:29,078 --> 01:07:31,914
I made the soup thicker

1845
01:07:31,981 --> 01:07:36,252
to let you eat everything in the soup
as you scoop up a spoonful.

1846
01:07:36,318 --> 01:07:37,953
That's why it's thicker.

1847
01:07:38,521 --> 01:07:41,924
SIPPING ON THE SOUP ENDLESSLY

1848
01:07:43,325 --> 01:07:46,429
He has his nose in the bowl.
It must be good.

1849
01:07:46,495 --> 01:07:48,130
-Are you hungover from yesterday?
-Wait.

1850
01:07:48,197 --> 01:07:52,401
-Look at him right now.
-Are you here to relieve the hangover?

1851
01:07:52,468 --> 01:07:53,436
This is so good.

1852
01:07:53,502 --> 01:07:55,004
He enjoyed that the most.

1853
01:07:55,671 --> 01:07:58,340
-Do you like it?
-Yes, it's so good.

1854
01:07:58,407 --> 01:08:00,209
You can have everything.

1855
01:08:00,276 --> 01:08:02,812
I like seeing both of you eat well.

1856
01:08:02,878 --> 01:08:04,847
He found what he likes.

1857
01:08:04,914 --> 01:08:07,183
This is something I really…

1858
01:08:07,783 --> 01:08:10,119
THE PROFESSOR GIVES HER TOP MARKS

1859
01:08:10,319 --> 01:08:11,954
YOU'RE THE BEST, EUN-YEONG

1860
01:08:12,021 --> 01:08:14,557
Is it because these were finely ground?

1861
01:08:14,623 --> 01:08:17,460
What's this thing that feels like rice?

1862
01:08:17,526 --> 01:08:20,763
<i>When green onions get deep-fried,</i>
<i>it can turn crunchy</i>

1863
01:08:20,830 --> 01:08:23,365
and add that kind of texture.

1864
01:08:23,432 --> 01:08:25,601
You threw in different textures.

1865
01:08:25,668 --> 01:08:28,037
-It's so good.
-He looks pleased.

1866
01:08:28,104 --> 01:08:29,672
Yes, it was pleasing.

1867
01:08:29,738 --> 01:08:32,074
He just had something warm.

1868
01:08:32,141 --> 01:08:35,711
Next, a dish made by Chef Nam-no.

1869
01:08:35,778 --> 01:08:37,413
A Plus Please, for Sabayon.

1870
01:08:37,480 --> 01:08:39,949
DUMPLING, CHICKEN, AND HAMBURGER STEAK

1871
01:08:40,549 --> 01:08:44,753
WITH HIGH-PROTEIN TOFU NOODLES
AND CARROT SABAYON

1872
01:08:45,454 --> 01:08:49,658
CHEF YOON NAM-NO'S
A PLUS PLEASE, FOR SABAYON

1873
01:08:50,226 --> 01:08:52,328
Can you let me sprinkle
a bit of broccoli powder?

1874
01:08:52,394 --> 01:08:53,629
Go ahead.

1875
01:08:53,696 --> 01:08:56,031
Chef Nam-no wants to sprinkle something.

1876
01:08:56,098 --> 01:08:58,968
Professor, may I sprinkle
some healthy broccoli powder?

1877
01:08:59,034 --> 01:09:00,302
-Sure.
-Is there a difference?

1878
01:09:00,369 --> 01:09:03,339
-Just that?
-He'll do that and insist it's healthy.

1879
01:09:03,405 --> 01:09:04,874
That only works in your mind!

1880
01:09:04,940 --> 01:09:05,941
Will that change things?

1881
01:09:06,342 --> 01:09:08,077
CRYING

1882
01:09:08,144 --> 01:09:10,112
Back in school,
there was always that one kid

1883
01:09:10,179 --> 01:09:12,948
who could never figure out
the intention behind a test question.

1884
01:09:13,015 --> 01:09:14,383
That's true.

1885
01:09:14,450 --> 01:09:16,085
He wants to make it look healthy.

1886
01:09:16,152 --> 01:09:17,553
-I see.
-Is that healthy?

1887
01:09:17,620 --> 01:09:21,357
-Gosh, now healthy. It's now green.
-How healthy is that?

1888
01:09:21,423 --> 01:09:23,792
-That looks healthy.
-Oh, my. How healthy.

1889
01:09:23,859 --> 01:09:24,793
In my opinion,

1890
01:09:24,860 --> 01:09:28,264
it may appear healthier,
but it will not help with its taste.

1891
01:09:28,964 --> 01:09:30,933
Is he trying to fool us with the visual?

1892
01:09:31,000 --> 01:09:33,068
He made a hole in the middle
and added stuff.

1893
01:09:33,135 --> 01:09:34,470
-Is it cooked?
-A little bit.

1894
01:09:34,537 --> 01:09:36,739
Is it cooked all the way inside?

1895
01:09:36,805 --> 01:09:37,907
Let's see the middle.

1896
01:09:41,844 --> 01:09:43,579
It's cooked. It's cooked nicely.

1897
01:09:43,646 --> 01:09:45,714
-Is it?
-It looks cooked.

1898
01:09:45,781 --> 01:09:48,284
I added dumplings and some chicken breast
on the inside.

1899
01:09:48,350 --> 01:09:49,318
Dumplings?

1900
01:09:49,385 --> 01:09:52,655
-There are dumplings inside?
-I mixed chicken and dumplings.

1901
01:09:52,721 --> 01:09:54,056
-Dumplings?
-It's fully cooked.

1902
01:09:54,123 --> 01:09:56,392
-It looks good.
-This is the key.

1903
01:09:56,458 --> 01:10:00,796
-Nam-no is a hard-working student.
-He is.

1904
01:10:00,863 --> 01:10:02,898
But he studied outside
of what the exam covered.

1905
01:10:02,965 --> 01:10:05,601
-Only irrelevant stuff.
-It wasn't on the exam.

1906
01:10:06,101 --> 01:10:07,703
POOR GUY…

1907
01:10:07,770 --> 01:10:09,705
But this can't be bad.

1908
01:10:09,772 --> 01:10:12,241
-First, please try it.
-It looks good though.

1909
01:10:12,308 --> 01:10:14,443
He tries hard. He just doesn't know how.

1910
01:10:14,510 --> 01:10:15,978
There are those guys.

1911
01:10:16,045 --> 01:10:17,947
It's like I'm eating a hamburger patty.

1912
01:10:18,647 --> 01:10:21,317
He did the homework on another page.

1913
01:10:21,383 --> 01:10:22,218
So?

1914
01:10:22,618 --> 01:10:24,086
CURIOUS

1915
01:10:26,722 --> 01:10:28,424
What does he mean by that face?

1916
01:10:28,490 --> 01:10:30,226
THE PROFESSOR'S INCOMPREHENSIBLE FACE

1917
01:10:30,793 --> 01:10:33,295
CAN'T HOLD BACK HER CURIOSITY
AND TAKES A BITE

1918
01:10:33,862 --> 01:10:36,398
It just can't be bad.

1919
01:10:36,465 --> 01:10:37,766
I can't believe it.

1920
01:10:37,833 --> 01:10:39,435
He's amazed.

1921
01:10:39,501 --> 01:10:40,769
It's good.

1922
01:10:40,836 --> 01:10:42,538
Both sides find the dish delicious.

1923
01:10:44,006 --> 01:10:46,408
A SPOONFUL OF THE SAUCE

1924
01:10:47,176 --> 01:10:51,180
The butter flavor in the sauce is amazing.

1925
01:10:51,247 --> 01:10:54,250
Yes, and he used the butter in the sauce,

1926
01:10:54,316 --> 01:10:57,653
something we don't just scoop up and eat.

1927
01:10:57,720 --> 01:11:01,123
-Of course.
-So it must be healthier than it seems.

1928
01:11:01,190 --> 01:11:03,726
-He used carrot juice and tofu noodles.
-He did.

1929
01:11:03,792 --> 01:11:05,928
Nothing about this is bad for you.

1930
01:11:05,995 --> 01:11:07,029
-You're right.
-Yes.

1931
01:11:07,096 --> 01:11:08,764
And he had to cook with convenience food.

1932
01:11:08,831 --> 01:11:11,100
-If you enjoy it, it's healthy for you.
-Yes.

1933
01:11:13,636 --> 01:11:15,671
He's not getting tested on bulking up.

1934
01:11:15,738 --> 01:11:18,107
This isn't what we were getting tested on?

1935
01:11:18,173 --> 01:11:19,141
What do I do?

1936
01:11:19,208 --> 01:11:20,476
It wasn't.

1937
01:11:21,644 --> 01:11:24,413
-I mean, look at this.
-Yes.

1938
01:11:24,480 --> 01:11:26,649
That's something you eat

1939
01:11:26,715 --> 01:11:29,685
to regain your energy
after you're discharged from a hospital.

1940
01:11:29,752 --> 01:11:31,654
-After you're discharged?
-For your stamina.

1941
01:11:31,720 --> 01:11:34,857
You barely eat one meal a day,

1942
01:11:34,923 --> 01:11:37,593
so I wanted to cook you
a high-calorie hearty meal.

1943
01:11:37,660 --> 01:11:39,895
-That makes sense.
-But that wasn't the test.

1944
01:11:42,164 --> 01:11:45,601
This is comforting in a whole new way.

1945
01:11:45,668 --> 01:11:47,236
Is it comforting in another way?

1946
01:11:47,303 --> 01:11:49,371
I'd eat this for lunch.

1947
01:11:49,438 --> 01:11:51,206
-Yes.
-For lunch.

1948
01:11:51,273 --> 01:11:52,908
-Something hearty?
-It looks good.

1949
01:11:52,975 --> 01:11:56,078
When I must spend lots of calories,
like before I work out.

1950
01:11:56,145 --> 01:11:57,479
A GOOD DISH TO BURN CALORIES

1951
01:11:57,913 --> 01:11:58,847
PRACTICAL ASSIGNMENT
TASTE: A PLUS

1952
01:11:58,914 --> 01:12:00,516
-It's really good.
-Is it really?

1953
01:12:00,582 --> 01:12:02,718
Non-Korean kids would love it.

1954
01:12:02,785 --> 01:12:04,253
-Non-Korean kids?
-Yes.

1955
01:12:04,320 --> 01:12:06,989
It'll be a huge hit in America.

1956
01:12:07,056 --> 01:12:09,525
He'll make it big if this becomes global.

1957
01:12:09,591 --> 01:12:11,694
After all, <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>
is a global show.

1958
01:12:11,760 --> 01:12:12,594
Of course.

1959
01:12:12,661 --> 01:12:14,363
We definitely are.

1960
01:12:14,430 --> 01:12:17,433
I was mostly full,
but I finished your dish.

1961
01:12:18,100 --> 01:12:20,569
-It must be heavy yet good.
-It has to be good.

1962
01:12:20,636 --> 01:12:25,174
<i>-Did you use crackers, not breadcrumbs?</i>
<i>-Yes, I used crackers.</i>

1963
01:12:25,240 --> 01:12:26,642
That was the kick.

1964
01:12:26,709 --> 01:12:30,279
It gives you that nice texture
which you can chew on.

1965
01:12:30,346 --> 01:12:32,114
-Anyway, this is really good.
-It really is.

1966
01:12:32,581 --> 01:12:34,717
STARTING TO GET NERVOUS…

1967
01:12:34,783 --> 01:12:37,820
They were to make something healthy
using convenience food,

1968
01:12:37,886 --> 01:12:41,457
and many of the ingredients he used
were true to the convenience factor.

1969
01:12:41,523 --> 01:12:43,058
Professor, you didn't know

1970
01:12:43,125 --> 01:12:44,793
what you were going to do

1971
01:12:44,860 --> 01:12:48,097
-with the <i>dongtae-tang</i>, and I handled it.
-Yes.

1972
01:12:48,163 --> 01:12:50,499
-The pollack soup?
-Professor, I got rid of it.

1973
01:12:50,566 --> 01:12:54,636
The assignment wasn't that
you were to get rid of his ingredients.

1974
01:12:54,703 --> 01:12:57,740
-You were to use convenience food.
-You had to use it, not get rid of it.

1975
01:12:57,806 --> 01:12:59,641
Both were so…

1976
01:12:59,708 --> 01:13:01,343
Which was more in line
with the professor's intentions?

1977
01:13:01,410 --> 01:13:04,513
-The scholarship only goes to one.
-It must be hard.

1978
01:13:04,580 --> 01:13:05,647
Both chefs are desperate.

1979
01:13:05,714 --> 01:13:08,016
-Please, Professor.
-Professor!

1980
01:13:08,083 --> 01:13:09,451
I really need an A!

1981
01:13:09,518 --> 01:13:10,753
BEATS EUN-YEONG TO IT

1982
01:13:10,819 --> 01:13:12,154
I really need an A plus!

1983
01:13:12,221 --> 01:13:14,656
-They both need it.
-I've never received a scholarship before!

1984
01:13:14,723 --> 01:13:16,358
-Oh, no.
-Eun-yeong and Nam-no.

1985
01:13:16,425 --> 01:13:19,828
-My family is struggling!
-She's even praying

1986
01:13:19,895 --> 01:13:21,630
Please give me an A, Professor!

1987
01:13:21,697 --> 01:13:24,733
Professor, my family is struggling!
I need the scholarship.

1988
01:13:24,800 --> 01:13:27,703
-Her family is struggling?
-Hey, come on!

1989
01:13:27,770 --> 01:13:29,037
She's taking things too far.

1990
01:13:29,104 --> 01:13:30,606
Her family is struggling?

1991
01:13:30,672 --> 01:13:31,907
-What's with you?
-That was a lot.

1992
01:13:31,974 --> 01:13:33,876
I know you're desperate, but come on.

1993
01:13:33,942 --> 01:13:36,211
I'm truly from a humble background.

1994
01:13:36,278 --> 01:13:38,080
-My family too.
-Both from humble families.

1995
01:13:38,147 --> 01:13:39,715
I'm sorry to stop you,

1996
01:13:39,782 --> 01:13:42,484
but he already made his choice
before all the yapping.

1997
01:13:43,051 --> 01:13:44,553
-He did?
-My gosh.

1998
01:13:45,754 --> 01:13:47,589
LOOKS

1999
01:13:47,823 --> 01:13:50,092
GOSH! (I PRESSED IT!)

2000
01:13:50,159 --> 01:13:51,326
Are you serious?

2001
01:13:51,393 --> 01:13:52,628
-What the heck?
-Before all that.

2002
01:13:52,694 --> 01:13:54,763
-I brought my family into this.
-He already did.

2003
01:13:54,830 --> 01:13:57,866
-He did it already.
-Professor, you decide so quickly.

2004
01:13:57,933 --> 01:14:00,469
He's more decisive than he seems.

2005
01:14:00,536 --> 01:14:03,138
He made his choice
before you brought up your family.

2006
01:14:03,205 --> 01:14:05,374
Let's find out the result.

2007
01:14:05,441 --> 01:14:07,209
Both students are desperate for a star.

2008
01:14:07,276 --> 01:14:08,777
Make a Healthy Dish.

2009
01:14:08,844 --> 01:14:12,581
-Who had better problem comprehension?
-This is so hard.

2010
01:14:12,648 --> 01:14:14,049
Was it Yoon Nam-no

2011
01:14:14,116 --> 01:14:15,350
or Park Eun-yeong?

2012
01:14:15,417 --> 01:14:19,822
Who'll take the scholarship,
the star, as well as the whiskey?

2013
01:14:19,888 --> 01:14:22,090
Who won?

2014
01:14:22,157 --> 01:14:25,360
Who did the professor give his star to?

2015
01:14:25,427 --> 01:14:27,095
CHEF PARK EUN-YEONG WINS

2016
01:14:27,162 --> 01:14:29,231
CHEF PARK EUN-YEONG'S
ATTACK YOON NAM-NO WINS

2017
01:14:29,298 --> 01:14:31,967
Park Eun-yeong wins! Eun-yeong!

2018
01:14:32,034 --> 01:14:34,069
Eun-yeong became the winner.

2019
01:14:34,436 --> 01:14:36,305
RELIEVED

2020
01:14:36,872 --> 01:14:38,106
Is your family struggling?

2021
01:14:38,173 --> 01:14:39,708
Yes, I had a tough childhood.

2022
01:14:39,775 --> 01:14:42,744
It was difficult to decide
on one of the two,

2023
01:14:42,811 --> 01:14:46,682
but I felt deeply comforted
after eating her dish.

2024
01:14:46,748 --> 01:14:48,650
Thank you. It was heartwarming.

2025
01:14:48,717 --> 01:14:51,587
-His nose was buried in the soup.
-He did that.

2026
01:14:51,653 --> 01:14:54,056
I knew she'd win then.
It must've been that good.

2027
01:14:54,122 --> 01:14:56,325
-I thought it was over.
-Yes.

2028
01:14:56,391 --> 01:15:00,562
Chef Park Eun-yeong is the winner.
Please put a star on her.

2029
01:15:01,230 --> 01:15:03,131
CONGRATS, EUN-YEONG

2030
01:15:03,198 --> 01:15:06,235
Please give her a star and this prize too.

2031
01:15:06,301 --> 01:15:07,503
A STAR FOR THE SCHOLARSHIP STUDENT

2032
01:15:07,569 --> 01:15:10,272
-Thank you.
-Ji-tae chose Chef Eun-yeong's dish.

2033
01:15:10,339 --> 01:15:13,108
-And the whiskey.
-The whiskey too.

2034
01:15:13,175 --> 01:15:14,843
Congratulations!

2035
01:15:14,910 --> 01:15:15,944
Thank you.

2036
01:15:16,011 --> 01:15:17,346
STAY TUNED FOR THE PREVIEW

2037
01:15:17,412 --> 01:15:19,314
She's smiling like a pageant queen.

2038
01:15:19,882 --> 01:15:22,284
THE LITTLE BRO TAKES A PICTURE
FOR THE BIG SIS

2039
01:15:22,784 --> 01:15:27,022
Please welcome today's fridge owners,
Kim Young-ok and Park Jun-myun!

2040
01:15:27,089 --> 01:15:29,491
She's the eldest active female actor.

2041
01:15:29,558 --> 01:15:30,492
But it turns out…

2042
01:15:30,559 --> 01:15:32,494
<i>Malatang. Tanghulu.</i> Salt bread.

2043
01:15:32,561 --> 01:15:33,395
SURPRISED

2044
01:15:33,462 --> 01:15:35,364
Those were all so delicious.

2045
01:15:35,430 --> 01:15:37,065
Do you know any recent buzzwords?

2046
01:15:37,132 --> 01:15:39,167
Deadass pissed.
Deadass mad. Deadass annoyed.

2047
01:15:39,234 --> 01:15:40,302
WHAT ARE WE HEARING?

2048
01:15:40,369 --> 01:15:41,737
Reality check. Something like that.

2049
01:15:41,803 --> 01:15:43,238
SHOWING OFF HER MILLENNIAL
AND EVEN GEN Z SIDES

2050
01:15:43,305 --> 01:15:46,408
They became the biggest enemies
after their time in <i>Culinary Class Wars.</i>

2051
01:15:46,475 --> 01:15:47,576
<i>I won't help him anymore.</i>

2052
01:15:47,643 --> 01:15:48,777
<i>Without helping?</i>

2053
01:15:48,844 --> 01:15:50,512
He seems a bit flustered.

2054
01:15:50,579 --> 01:15:51,813
It'd be nice if someone held this.

2055
01:15:51,880 --> 01:15:53,448
He can't do a thing without Sam!

2056
01:15:53,515 --> 01:15:54,449
Can you grab a paper towel?

2057
01:15:54,516 --> 01:15:55,851
Why are you helping him?

2058
01:15:55,918 --> 01:15:57,185
My body moved automatically.

2059
01:15:57,252 --> 01:15:58,620
IS THAT THE TEAM ROUND'S AFTERMATH?

2060
01:15:58,687 --> 01:16:01,723
I hoped you would make me something
that a queen would eat.

2061
01:16:01,790 --> 01:16:03,725
It's a return match
after the previous championship.

2062
01:16:03,792 --> 01:16:06,061
Grand Queen Dowager.

2063
01:16:06,261 --> 01:16:07,296
SEIZING THE ROUND BY DANCING

2064
01:16:07,362 --> 01:16:09,398
-It's on fire! What's wrong?
-Hey!

2065
01:16:09,464 --> 01:16:10,832
-It's on fire.
-Things aren't working out.

2066
01:16:10,899 --> 01:16:11,833
How scary.

2067
01:16:11,900 --> 01:16:13,201
Are you okay, Chef Hyun-suk?

2068
01:16:13,268 --> 01:16:14,570
WHO'LL WIN THE RETURN MATCH?

2069
01:16:14,636 --> 01:16:15,871
I wonder what it's like.

2070
01:16:15,938 --> 01:16:17,973
How did you make this sauce?

2071
01:16:18,040 --> 01:16:19,241
It's so good.

2072
01:16:19,308 --> 01:16:21,076
-I'm speechless.
-She's speechless.

2073
01:16:21,143 --> 01:16:22,077
WHAT MADE HER SPEECHLESS?

2074
01:16:34,690 --> 01:16:39,461
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
